is rejected three days later.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Yuen |first1=Sin |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/singapolitics/josephine-teo-rejects-sdps-bid-to-cancel-correction-notices |title=SDP's bid to get correction order cancelled rejected |date=6 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 4 January - The [[Sembawang Hot Spring Park]] reopens with refreshed facilities, the only natural hot spring in Singapore.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Mohan |first1=Matthew |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/sembawang-hot-spring-park-reopens-cascading-pool-floral-walk-12232820 |title=Sembawang Hot Spring Park reopens with cascading pool, cafe and floral walk |website=CNA |access-date=4 January 2020 |date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n* 6 January - [[Eunoia Junior College]] moves to its new campus in Bishan, making it Singapore's first high-rise Junior College. It is also integrated with the future Bishan North Community Club.<ref>{{cite web |title=Classes to begin at Singapore's first high-rise junior college on Jan 6 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/classes-to-begin-at-singapores-first-high-rise-junior-college-on-jan-6 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=13 January 2020 |date=2 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Menon |first1=Malavika |title=Eunoia Junior College moves in to new Bishan campus |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/education/eunoia-junior-college-moves-in-to-new-campus-in-sin-ming-avenue |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=13 January 2020 |date=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n* 8 January - The Singapore Democratic Party (SDP) appeals the correction in court, the first such court challenge.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Yuen |first1=Sin |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/singapolitics/sdp-appeals-against-correction-notices-by-manpower-ministry-first-court |title=SDP appeals against correction notices by Manpower Ministry in first court challenge of fake news law |date=8 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> The SDP requests to have the case held in open court due to public interest,<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Kurohi |first1=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/case-against-pofma-corrections-should-be-heard-in-open-court-sdp |title=Case against Pofma corrections should be heard in open court: SDP |date=13 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> which is subsequently rejected in view of rules.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Kurohi |first1=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/high-court-rejects-sdps-application-to-have-pofma-case-heard-in-open-court |title=High Court rejects SDP's application to have Pofma case heard in open court |date=16 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> After the hearing, the Attorney-General's Chambers (AGC) said that SDP made misleading statements,<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Kurohi |first1=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/pofma-challenge-agc-seeks-further-hearing-says-sdp-mischaracterised-its-arguments |title=Pofma challenge: AGC seeks further hearing, says SDP mischaracterised its arguments |date=20 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> which the SDP promised to correct later on.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tee |first1=Zhuo |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/sdp-promises-to-correct-article-that-mis-characterises-agcs-position |title=SDP promises to correct article that mischaracterises AGC's position: AGC |date=23 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 22 January - [[Lawyers for Liberty]] (LFL) and three parties who shared LFL's posts are issued correction notices against false allegations on the [[death penalty]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/mha-refutes-malaysia-ngos-allegations-against-spores-execution-method-to |title=MHA refutes Malaysia NGO's claims against S'pore's execution method, issues Pofma correction orders against parties |date=22 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> All parties complied except for LFL, causing the [[Info-communications Media Development Authority|Infocomm Media Development Authority]] to block LFL website the following day.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tee |first1=Zhuo |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/imda-to-block-malaysian-ngo-website-after-it-fails-to-comply-with-pofma-correction-mci |title=IMDA to block Malaysian NGO website after it fails to comply with Pofma correction: MCI |date=23 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> LFL has since filed a court case in Malaysia.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=H. Rodzi |first1=Nadirah |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/malaysian-rights-group-sues-minister-k-shanmugam-in-kl-over-pofma-correction-order |title=Malaysian rights group sues Minister K Shanmugam in KL over Pofma correction order |date=24 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> [[The Online Citizen]] appealed the order, which is rejected on 24 January.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/home-affairs-minister-rejects-tocs-application-to-cancel-pofma-correction-order |title=Home Affairs Minister Shanmugam rejects TOC's application to cancel Pofma correction order |date=24 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 30 January - [[Mediacorp]] renames its digital media platforms Toggle, MeRadio and MeClub to [[meWatch]], meListen and meRewards respectively.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mediacorp rolls out meWATCH, meLISTEN, meREWARDS and meCONNECT |url=https://www.mediacorp.sg/en/mediacorp-in-the-news/media-releases/mediacorp-rolls-out-mewatch-melisten-merewards-and-meconnect-12369778 |website=Mediacorp |accessdate=30 January 2020 |date=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n* 31 January - \n**The first stage of the [[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line]] (spanning from [[Woodlands North MRT station|Woodlands North]] to [[Woodlands South MRT station|Woodlands South]]) opens.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Vanessa |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/first-three-stations-of-thomson-east-coast-line-to-begin-service-on-jan-31-free |title=First three stations of Thomson-East Coast Line to begin service on Jan 31; free travel for commuters for three days |website=The Straits Times |access-date=11 December 2019 |date=11 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Kai Yi |title=3 stations on Thomson-East Coast Line begin operations |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/3-stations-on-thomson-east-coast-line-begin-operations |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=15 January 2020 |date=31 January 2020}}</ref> In addition, a new MRT map is rolled out at all stations with the [[Circle MRT line]] as a focus.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/new-mrt-network-map-be-rolled-out-all-stations-jan-31 |title=New MRT network map to be rolled out at all stations by Jan 31 |website=Today |access-date=11 December 2019 |date=11 December 2019}}</ref>\n**[[Cold Stone Creamery]] closes after being in Singapore for 10 years.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Quek |first1=Eunice |title=Cold Stone Creamery exits Singapore on Jan 31 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/food/cold-stone-creamery-exits-singapore-on-jan-31 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=15 January 2020 |date=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n* 5 February - The Singapore Democratic Party lost the appeal, with the court ruling that a statement has to be proven false by the Government after a correction is issued.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tham |first1=Yuen-C |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/first-court-challenge-against-fake-news-law-fails-high-court-dismisses-sdps-appeal |title=First court challenge against fake news law fails; High Court dismisses SDP's appeal |date=5 February 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n* 10 March - An extension of the [[Cross Island MRT line]] is announced. Spanning {{Convert|7.3|km|miles|abbr=in}} from [[Pasir Ris MRT station|Pasir Ris]] to [[Punggol MRT/LRT station|Punggol]], the four-station extension will be completed by 2031.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Kai Yi |title=Punggol residents to get four more train stations by 2031 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/punggol-residents-to-get-four-more-train-stations-by-2031 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=10 March 2020 |date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/punggol-extension-cross-island-line-mrt-stations-construction-12521038|title=Punggol extension on Cross Island Line to begin construction in 2022|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310042859/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/punggol-extension-cross-island-line-mrt-stations-construction-12521038| archive-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 13 March - [[2020 Singaporean general election|General Elections]]: The [[List of Singaporean electoral divisions|Electoral Boundaries Review Committee report]] is released. The 14th parliament will consist of 93 members from 31 constituencies (14 Single Member Constituencies and 17 Group Representation Constituencies), up from 89 seats from the current 29 constituencies. In addition, six-member GRCs will be abolished, with the maximum being five MPs in each GRC.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Sim |first1=Royston |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/singapore-ge-new-electoral-boundaries-announced-14-smcs-17-grcs-in-next-election |title=Singapore GE: New electoral boundaries announced; 14 SMCs, 17 GRCs in next election |website=The Straits Times |access-date=13 March 2020 |date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/general-election-ebrc-electoral-boundaries-grc-smc-12535200|title=More electoral divisions, no 6-member GRCs in coming election: EBRC report|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=13 March 2020|date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 31 March - [[Liang Court]], a shopping mall in [[Clarke Quay]], ceases operation.\n\n===Predicted and scheduled events===\n* 9 June - [[Lotte Corporation|Lotte Duty Free]] will take over [[DFS Group]]'s [[Changi Airport]] liquor and tobacco stores<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ang |first1=Prisca |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/lotte-duty-free-to-take-over-dfs-liquor-and-tobacco-stores-in-changi-airport-from-june |title=Lotte Duty Free to take over DFS liquor and tobacco stores in Changi Airport from June 2020 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=25 October 2019 |date=24 October 2019}}</ref> as the latter ends its 39-year tenancy due to a challenging environment.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Heng |first1=Melissa |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/dfs-pulls-out-of-changi-airports-liquor-tobacco-business-all-stores-to-shut-in |title=DFS stores in Changi Airport to close in June 2020; South Korea's Shilla and Lotte among 3 new bidders |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=25 October 2019 |date=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n* Kallang Polyclinic, connected to Kwong Wai Shiu Hospital will open.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Baharudin |first1=Hariz |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/kwong-wai-shiu-hospital-nursing-home-opens-after-100m-facelift |title=Kwong Wai Shiu Hospital nursing home opens after $96m facelift |website=The Straits Times |access-date=7 July 2019 |date=6 October 2018}}</ref> \n* The second stage of the [[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line]] (spanning from [[Springleaf MRT station|Springleaf]] to [[Caldecott MRT station|Caldecott]]) will open.\n*[[2020 Singaporean general election]]\n\n==Deaths==\n* 1 January - [[Ng Jui Ping]], former [[Chief of Defence Force (Singapore)|Chief of Defence Force]] (b. 1948).<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapores-second-chief-of-defence-force-ng-jui-ping-dies-at-71|title = Singapore's second Chief of Defence Force Ng Jui Ping dies at 71|work = [[The Straits Times]]|date = 1 January 2020|accessdate = 1 January 2020|last = Menon|first = Malavika}}</ref>\n* 9 January -\n**[[Jo Heng]], lyricist (b. 1960).<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Ang |first1=Benson |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/xinyao-lyricist-jo-heng-who-wrote-lyrics-for-singers-like-jacky-cheung-and |title=Xinyao lyricist Jo Heng, who wrote lyrics for singers like Jacky Cheung and Eric Moo, dies at 59 |date=9 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Yong Pung How]] - 2nd [[Chief Justice of Singapore]] (b. 1926).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lum |first1=Selina |title=Singapore's former chief justice Yong Pung How dies, aged 93 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/former-chief-justice-yong-pung-how-dies-he-was-93 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=9 January 2019 |date=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Singapore}}\n{{Year in Asia |2020}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2020s in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2020 in Asia|Singapore]]\n[[Category:2020 by country|Singapore]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Singapore-related events in 2020}}\n{{Dynamic list}}\n{{Year in Singapore |2020}}\nThe following lists events that happened during [[2020]] '''in the [[Singapore|Republic of Singapore]]'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n*[[President of Singapore|President]]: [[Halimah Yacob]] \n*[[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]]: [[Lee Hsien Loong]]\n\n== Events == <!--Editors NOTE: Please do not include annual events, only ONE-OFF notable events; feel free to add on as day is confirmed, but once the day has passed, move the event to the respective months.-->\n\n===January===\n* 1 January - \n**The [[smoking age]] increases to 20.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Choo |first1=Felicia |title=Minimum legal age for smoking raised to 19 from Jan 1 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/minimum-legal-age-for-tobacco-raised-to-19-years-old-from-jan-1-2019 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=12 December 2019 |date=30 December 2018}}</ref>\n**The [[Goods and Services Tax (Singapore)|Goods and Services Tax]] extends to digital services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/budget-2018-gst-to-be-imposed-on-digital-services-from-2020-9970756|title=Budget 2018: GST to be imposed on digital services from 2020|date=2018-02-19|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n**The Criminal Law Reform Act comes into force, amending laws in the [[Penal Code (Singapore)|Penal Code]] with a new fire offence created to prevent improper disposal of lighted materials. Amendments to the [[Protection from Harassment Act (Singapore)|Protection from Harassment Act]] also comes into force.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ng |first1=Charmaine |title=Watch that cigarette butt and BBQ embers - firestarters to feel more heat from the law from Jan 1 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/watch-that-cigarette-butt-and-bbq-embers-firestarters-to-feel-more-heat-from |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=31 December 2019 |date=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n* 2 January and ongoing - [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore|COVID-19 pandemic]]:\n**2 January - The [[Ministry of Health (Singapore)|Ministry of Health]] (MOH) issued a health advisory on a pneumonia outbreak in [[Wuhan]].<ref name=\"ST2Jan\">{{cite web |last1=Goh |first1=Timothy |title=Travellers arriving at Changi Airport from Wuhan to undergo temperature screening after pneumonia outbreak |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/ministry-of-health-issues-advisory-on-viral-pneumonia-outbreak-in-chinas-wuhan |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=15 January 2020 |date=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n**3 January - Temperauture checks are introduced for passengers arriving at [[Changi Airport]] from [[Wuhan]].<ref name=\"ST2Jan\"/>\n**4 January - The first suspected case is reported,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chang |first1=Ai-Lien |title=Wuhan pneumonia: First suspected case reported in Singapore |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/wuhan-pneumonia-first-suspect-case-identified-here |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=15 January 2020 |date=4 January 2020}}</ref> later confirmed not linked and due to [[Human orthopneumovirus|RSV]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chong |first1=Clara |title=3-year-old girl with pneumonia and travel history to Wuhan is not linked to outbreak in China: MOH |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/3-year-old-girl-with-pneumonia-and-travel-history-to-wuhan-is-not-linked-to-outbreak-in |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=15 January 2020 |date=5 January 2020}}</ref>\n**10 January - The second suspected case is reported,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Khalik |first1=Salma |title=China national suspected of having Wuhan bug has been isolated in Singapore |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/china-national-suspected-of-having-wuhan-bug-has-been-isolated-in-singapore |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=15 January 2020 |date=10 January 2020}}</ref> later confirmed not linked.<ref>{{cite web |title=Second suspected case of Wuhan virus in Singapore tests negative |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/second-suspected-case-of-wuhan-virus-in-singapore-tests-negative |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=15 January 2020 |date=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n**16 January - The third suspected case is reported,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lai |first1=Linette |title=Third suspected Wuhan virus case detected in Singapore, man isolated as precaution |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/3rd-suspected-wuhan-virus-case-detected-in-singapore-man-isolated-as-precaution |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=16 January 2020 |date=16 January 2020}}</ref> since tested negative.<ref name=\"Update 1\"/>\n**17 January - Two suspected cases are reported, bringing the number to five.<ref name=\"Update 1\">{{cite web |last1=Chong |first1=Clara |title=2 more suspected Wuhan virus cases in Singapore; both isolated as precaution |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/2-more-suspected-wuhan-virus-cases-detected-in-singapore-both-isolated-as-precaution |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=20 January 2020 |date=17 January 2020}}</ref> Both cases have since tested negative.<ref name=\"Update 2\"/>\n**18 January - The sixth suspected case is reported,<ref name=\"Update 2\">{{cite web |title=New suspected Wuhan virus case in Singapore, remaining 5 have tested negative |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-suspected-wuhan-virus-case-in-singapore-remaining-five-have-tested-negative |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=20 January 2020 |date=18 January 2020}}</ref> since tested negative.<ref name=\"Update 3\"/>\n**20 January - The MOH extends temperature screening at Changi Airport to all travellers coming from China, as well as isolating individuals in hospital should they display symptoms. In addition, the seventh suspected case is reported,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/wuhan-pneumonia-virus-outbreak-china-travellers-singapore-12291456|title=Wuhan virus: All travellers arriving in Singapore from China to undergo temperature screening|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref name=\"Update 3\">{{cite web |last1=Yong |first1=Clement |title=Wuhan virus: Singapore expands temperature screening to all travellers arriving from China |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/moh-steps-up-measures-against-wuhan-virus-as-cny-approaches |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=20 January 2020 |date=20 January 2020}}</ref> since tested negative.<ref name=\"Update 4\">{{cite web |last1=Yong |first1=Clement |title=Wuhan virus: Singapore to isolate all travellers from China with pneumonia; 7th suspect tests negative |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/wuhan-virus-moh-widening-quarantine-measures-7th-suspect-tests-negative |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=21 January 2020 |date=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n**21 January - The MOH extends quarantine measures to all travellers arriving from China, taking effect the next day.<ref name=\"Update 4\"/>\n**22 January - Three suspected cases are detected, causing the MOH to form a multi-ministry taskforce on the virus. People are also advised to avoid non-essential travel to Wuhan in the meantime.<ref name=\"Update 5\">{{cite web |last1=Goh |first1=Timothy |title=Wuhan virus: MOH sets up multi-ministry taskforce, advises against non-essential trips to Wuhan |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/wuhan-virus-3-more-suspected-cases-in-singapore-avoid-non-essential-travel-to-wuhan |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=22 January 2020 |date=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n**23 January - The first case is confirmed, with preliminary tests showing positive results for another. Another 28 suspected cases are detected after enhanced testing. Border control measures will be tightened, with measures extended to land and sea checkpoints from the next day.<ref name=\"Update23Jan\">{{cite web |last1=Goh |first1=Timothy |last2=Toh |first2=Ting Wei |title=Singapore confirms first case of Wuhan virus; second case likely |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/singapore-confirms-first-case-of-wuhan-virus |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=23 January 2020 |date=23 January 2020}}</ref> Earlier on, the MOH advised against travel to Wuhan, later expanded to Hubei province.<ref>{{cite web |last=Yong |first=Clement |title=Wuhan virus: MOH expands travel advisory, now urges Singaporeans to avoid travel to Hubei province |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/wuhan-virus-avoid-travelling-to-wuhan-says-moh |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=23 January 2020}}</ref> [[Scoot]] has cancelled flights to Wuhan between 23 and 26 January over the virus outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |title=Scoot cancels flights to China's Wuhan over virus outbreak |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/wuhan-virus-scoot-cancels-flights-mtr-train-12309076 |website=CNA |accessdate=28 January 2020 |date=23 January 2020}}</ref> Schools have also asked parents to declare their travel plans and monitor their children's health. Other measures will also be taken to ensure the safety of students.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ang |first1=Hwee Min |title=Schools step up precautions after Wuhan virus case confirmed in Singapore |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/wuhan-virus-schools-declare-chinese-new-year-travel-plans-12310972 |website=CNA |accessdate=29 January 2020 |date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Teng |first1=Amelia |title=Wuhan virus: Singapore schools ask parents, staff to declare weekend travel plans |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/education/moe-and-pre-schools-ask-parents-and-staff-to-declare-weekend-travel-plans-to |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=29 January 2020 |date=23 January 2020}}</ref> [[Ministry of Defence (Singapore)|MINDEF]] has since issued two medical advisories to service personnel.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Low |first1=Dominic |title=Wuhan virus: Mindef issues two advisories for service personnel |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/wuhan-virus-mindef-issues-two-advisories-for-service-personnel |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=29 January 2020 |date=23 January 2020}}</ref> A patient was taken from [[Eastpoint Mall, Singapore|Eastpoint Mall]] to [[Tan Tock Seng Hospital]] after being suspected of having the virus.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/patient-suspected-having-wuhan-virus-taken-eastpoint-mall-tan-tock-seng-hospital |title=Patient suspected of having Wuhan virus taken from Eastpoint Mall to Tan Tock Seng Hospital |date=24 January 2020 |website=Today |access-date=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n**24 January - The [[Immigration and Checkpoints Authority]] and [[Maritime and Port Authority of Singapore]] implement temperature-taking from noon.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wuhan virus: Temperature screening begins at Woodlands, Tuas and sea checkpoints |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/wuhan-virus-woodlands-tuas-checkpoint-temperature-screening-12319724 |website=CNA |accessdate=29 January 2020 |date=24 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Baharudin |first1=Hariz |title=Wuhan virus: ICA implements temperature screening at Woodlands and Tuas checkpoints |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/temperature-screening-for-all-travellers-at-woodlands-and-tuas |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=29 January 2020 |date=24 January 2020}}</ref> Later that day, two more cases are confirmed. 44 suspected cases are reported, of which 13 are negative.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Khalik |first1=Salma |last2=Goh |first2=Timothy |title=Singapore confirms 2 more Wuhan virus cases, bringing total to 3 infected |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/singapore-confirms-2-more-wuhan-virus-cases-bringing-total-to-three-infected |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=29 January 2020 |date=24 January 2020}}</ref> Several holiday chalets and student hostels will be prepared as government quarantine centres.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Toh |first1=Ting Wei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/quarantine-places-including-chalets-being-prepared-as-singapore-fights-spread-of |title=Wuhan virus: Quarantine centres, including chalets, being prepared as Singapore fights spread of disease |date=24 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=27 January 2020}}</ref> In addition, several companies have since taken more precautions against the virus.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Iau |first1=Jean |last2=Wong |first2=Lester |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/wuhan-virus-comfortdelgro-stockpiles-masks-and-disinfectants-issue