|access-date=23 March 2020 |date=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n***[[Outward Bound Singapore]] camps in Pulau Ubin will be designated quarantine facilities.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cheow |first1=Sue-Ann |url=https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/obs-camps-be-used-quarantine-facilities |title=OBS camps to be used as quarantine facilities |date=30 January 2020 |website=The New Paper |access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n**4 February - Six new cases are confirmed, including the first cases of local transmission at Yong Thai Hang involving four people.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chang |first1=Ai-Lien |last2=Khalik |first2=Salma |title=Coronavirus: S'pore reports first cases of local transmission; 4 out of 6 new cases did not travel to China |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/coronavirus-spore-reports-first-cases-of-local-transmission-4-out-of-6-new-cases-did-not |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n**7 February - The Disease Outbreak Response System Condition (DORSCON) level is raised from Yellow to Orange after more cases with unclear origins surfaced.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chang |first1=Ai-Lien |last2=Khalik |first2=Salma |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/coronavirus-outbreak-alert-upped-to-orange-as-more-cases-surface-with-no-known-links-more |title=Coronavirus: Singapore ups outbreak alert to orange as more cases surface with no known links; more measures in force |access-date=14 March 2020 |website=The Straits Times |date=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n**21 March - The first two deaths are confirmed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Vanessa |title=Singapore reports first two coronavirus deaths: a 75-year-old Singaporean woman and 64-year old Indonesian man |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapore-reports-two-covid-19-deaths-health-minister-gan |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n**27 March - Singapore invokes the Infectious Diseases (COVID-19) movement control law, banning entertainment outlets, nightclubs and tuition centres, and restricting remaining building crowd density such as MRT and LRT stations, and shopping centres to one person per 16 square metres of space, failing which they will be asked to close. \n* 3 January - \n**An appeal by States Times Review to cancel the correction notices is rejected.<ref name=\"STR\">{{Cite web |last1=Kurohi |first1=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/states-times-reviews-application-to-cancel-pofma-order-rejected-sdp-files-separate |title=States Times Review's application to cancel Pofma order rejected; SDP files separate application |date=3 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[Singapore Democratic Party]] appeals to cancel the correction notices issued the previous month,<ref name=\"STR\"/> coming a day after it defended its posts.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Kurohi |first1=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/fake-news-law-sdp-defends-posts-says-it-will-apply-to-cancel-corrections-on-jan-3 |title=Fake news law: SDP defends posts, says it will apply to cancel correction notices; MOM says party should follow process |date=2 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> The request is rejected three days later.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Yuen |first1=Sin |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/singapolitics/josephine-teo-rejects-sdps-bid-to-cancel-correction-notices |title=SDP's bid to get correction order cancelled rejected |date=6 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 4 January - The [[Sembawang Hot Spring Park]] reopens with refreshed facilities, the only natural hot spring in Singapore.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Mohan |first1=Matthew |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/sembawang-hot-spring-park-reopens-cascading-pool-floral-walk-12232820 |title=Sembawang Hot Spring Park reopens with cascading pool, cafe and floral walk |website=CNA |access-date=4 January 2020 |date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n* 6 January - [[Eunoia Junior College]] moves to its new campus in Bishan, making it Singapore's first high-rise Junior College. It is also integrated with the future Bishan North Community Club.<ref>{{cite web |title=Classes to begin at Singapore's first high-rise junior college on Jan 6 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/classes-to-begin-at-singapores-first-high-rise-junior-college-on-jan-6 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=13 January 2020 |date=2 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Menon |first1=Malavika |title=Eunoia Junior College moves in to new Bishan campus |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/education/eunoia-junior-college-moves-in-to-new-campus-in-sin-ming-avenue |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=13 January 2020 |date=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n* 8 January - The Singapore Democratic Party (SDP) appeals the correction in court, the first such court challenge.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Yuen |first1=Sin |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/singapolitics/sdp-appeals-against-correction-notices-by-manpower-ministry-first-court |title=SDP appeals against correction notices by Manpower Ministry in first court challenge of fake news law |date=8 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> The SDP requests to have the case held in open court due to public interest,<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Kurohi |first1=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/case-against-pofma-corrections-should-be-heard-in-open-court-sdp |title=Case against Pofma corrections should be heard in open court: SDP |date=13 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> which is subsequently rejected in view of rules.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Kurohi |first1=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/high-court-rejects-sdps-application-to-have-pofma-case-heard-in-open-court |title=High Court rejects SDP's application to have Pofma case heard in open court |date=16 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=16 February 2020}}</ref> After the hearing, the Attorney-General's Chambers (AGC) said that SDP made misleading statements,<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Kurohi |first1=Rei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/pofma-challenge-agc-seeks-further-hearing-says-sdp-mischaracterised-its-arguments |title=Pofma challenge: AGC seeks further hearing, says SDP mischaracterised its arguments |date=20 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> which the SDP promised to correct later on.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tee |first1=Zhuo |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/sdp-promises-to-correct-article-that-mis-characterises-agcs-position |title=SDP promises to correct article that mischaracterises AGC's position: AGC |date=23 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 22 January - [[Lawyers for Liberty]] (LFL) and three parties who shared LFL's posts are issued correction notices against false allegations on the [[death penalty]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/mha-refutes-malaysia-ngos-allegations-against-spores-execution-method-to |title=MHA refutes Malaysia NGO's claims against S'pore's execution method, issues Pofma correction orders against parties |date=22 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> All parties complied except for LFL, causing the [[Info-communications Media Development Authority|Infocomm Media Development Authority]] to block LFL website the following day.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tee |first1=Zhuo |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/imda-to-block-malaysian-ngo-website-after-it-fails-to-comply-with-pofma-correction-mci |title=IMDA to block Malaysian NGO website after it fails to comply with Pofma correction: MCI |date=23 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> LFL has since filed a court case in Malaysia.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=H. Rodzi |first1=Nadirah |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/malaysian-rights-group-sues-minister-k-shanmugam-in-kl-over-pofma-correction-order |title=Malaysian rights group sues Minister K Shanmugam in KL over Pofma correction order |date=24 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref> [[The Online Citizen]] appealed the order, which is rejected on 24 January.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/home-affairs-minister-rejects-tocs-application-to-cancel-pofma-correction-order |title=Home Affairs Minister Shanmugam rejects TOC's application to cancel Pofma correction order |date=24 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 30 January - [[Mediacorp]] renames its digital media platforms Toggle, MeRadio and MeClub to [[meWatch]], meListen and meRewards respectively.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mediacorp rolls out meWATCH, meLISTEN, meREWARDS and meCONNECT |url=https://www.mediacorp.sg/en/mediacorp-in-the-news/media-releases/mediacorp-rolls-out-mewatch-melisten-merewards-and-meconnect-12369778 |website=Mediacorp |accessdate=30 January 2020 |date=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n* 31 January - \n**The first stage of the [[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line]] (spanning from [[Woodlands North MRT station|Woodlands North]] to [[Woodlands South MRT station|Woodlands South]]) opens.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Vanessa |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/first-three-stations-of-thomson-east-coast-line-to-begin-service-on-jan-31-free |title=First three stations of Thomson-East Coast Line to begin service on Jan 31; free travel for commuters for three days |website=The Straits Times |access-date=11 December 2019 |date=11 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Kai Yi |title=3 stations on Thomson-East Coast Line begin operations |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/3-stations-on-thomson-east-coast-line-begin-operations |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=15 January 2020 |date=31 January 2020}}</ref> In addition, a new MRT map is rolled out at all stations with the [[Circle MRT line]] as a focus.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/new-mrt-network-map-be-rolled-out-all-stations-jan-31 |title=New MRT network map to be rolled out at all stations by Jan 31 |website=Today |access-date=11 December 2019 |date=11 December 2019}}</ref>\n**[[Cold Stone Creamery]] closes after being in Singapore for 10 years.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Quek |first1=Eunice |title=Cold Stone Creamery exits Singapore on Jan 31 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/food/cold-stone-creamery-exits-singapore-on-jan-31 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=15 January 2020 |date=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n* 5 February - The Singapore Democratic Party lost the appeal, with the court ruling that a statement has to be proven false by the Government after a correction is issued.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tham |first1=Yuen-C |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/first-court-challenge-against-fake-news-law-fails-high-court-dismisses-sdps-appeal |title=First court challenge against fake news law fails; High Court dismisses SDP's appeal |date=5 February 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n* 10 March - An extension of the [[Cross Island MRT line]] is announced. Spanning {{Convert|7.3|km|miles|abbr=in}} from [[Pasir Ris MRT station|Pasir Ris]] to [[Punggol MRT/LRT station|Punggol]], the four-station extension will be completed by 2031.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wong |first1=Kai Yi |title=Punggol residents to get four more train stations by 2031 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/punggol-residents-to-get-four-more-train-stations-by-2031 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=10 March 2020 |date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/punggol-extension-cross-island-line-mrt-stations-construction-12521038|title=Punggol extension on Cross Island Line to begin construction in 2022|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310042859/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/punggol-extension-cross-island-line-mrt-stations-construction-12521038| archive-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 13 March - [[2020 Singaporean general election|General Elections]]: The [[List of Singaporean electoral divisions|Electoral Boundaries Review Committee report]] is released. The 14th parliament will consist of 93 members from 31 constituencies (14 Single Member Constituencies and 17 Group Representation Constituencies), up from 89 seats from the current 29 constituencies. In addition, six-member GRCs will be abolished, with the maximum being five MPs in each GRC.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Sim |first1=Royston |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/singapore-ge-new-electoral-boundaries-announced-14-smcs-17-grcs-in-next-election |title=Singapore GE: New electoral boundaries announced; 14 SMCs, 17 GRCs in next election |website=The Straits Times |access-date=13 March 2020 |date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/general-election-ebrc-electoral-boundaries-grc-smc-12535200|title=More electoral divisions, no 6-member GRCs in coming election: EBRC report|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=13 March 2020|date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 31 March - [[Liang Court]], a shopping mall in [[Clarke Quay]], ceases operation.\n\n===Predicted and scheduled events===\n* 9 June - [[Lotte Corporation|Lotte Duty Free]] will take over [[DFS Group]]'s [[Changi Airport]] liquor and tobacco stores<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ang |first1=Prisca |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/lotte-duty-free-to-take-over-dfs-liquor-and-tobacco-stores-in-changi-airport-from-june |title=Lotte Duty Free to take over DFS liquor and tobacco stores in Changi Airport from June 2020 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=25 October 2019 |date=24 October 2019}}</ref> as the latter ends its 39-year tenancy due to a challenging environment.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Heng |first1=Melissa |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/dfs-pulls-out-of-changi-airports-liquor-tobacco-business-all-stores-to-shut-in |title=DFS stores in Changi Airport to close in June 2020; South Korea's Shilla and Lotte among 3 new bidders |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=25 October 2019 |date=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n* Kallang Polyclinic, connected to Kwong Wai Shiu Hospital will open.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Baharudin |first1=Hariz |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/kwong-wai-shiu-hospital-nursing-home-opens-after-100m-facelift |title=Kwong Wai Shiu Hospital nursing home opens after $96m facelift |website=The Straits Times |access-date=7 July 2019 |date=6 October 2018}}</ref> \n* The second stage of the [[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line]] (spanning from [[Springleaf MRT station|Springleaf]] to [[Caldecott MRT station|Caldecott]]) will open.\n*[[2020 Singaporean general election]]\n\n==Deaths==\n* 1 January - [[Ng Jui Ping]], former [[Chief of Defence Force (Singapore)|Chief of Defence Force]] (b. 1948).<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapores-second-chief-of-defence-force-ng-jui-ping-dies-at-71|title = Singapore's second Chief of Defence Force Ng Jui Ping dies at 71|work = [[The Straits Times]]|date = 1 January 2020|accessdate = 1 January 2020|last = Menon|first = Malavika}}</ref>\n* 9 January -\n**[[Jo Heng]], lyricist (b. 1960).<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Ang |first1=Benson |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/xinyao-lyricist-jo-heng-who-wrote-lyrics-for-singers-like-jacky-cheung-and |title=Xinyao lyricist Jo Heng, who wrote lyrics for singers like Jacky Cheung and Eric Moo, dies at 59 |date=9 January 2020 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Yong Pung How]] - 2nd [[Chief Justice of Singapore]] (b. 1926).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lum |first1=Selina |title=Singapore's former chief justice Yong Pung How dies, aged 93 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/former-chief-justice-yong-pung-how-dies-he-was-93 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=9 January 2019 |date=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Singapore}}\n{{Year in Asia |2020}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2020s in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2020 in Asia|Singapore]]\n[[Category:2020 by country|Singapore]]\n", "name_user": "TheGreatSG'rean", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJanuary", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_in_Singapore"}
{"title_page": "Chinese imperialism", "text_new": "Over the last four thousand years Chinese [[imperialism]] and expansion has been a central feature of the history of East Asia. Since the recovery of Chinese strength in the late 20th century, the issues involved have been of concern to China's neighbors to the east.\n\n==Early Chinese expansions==\nIn Chinese political theory, relations between foreign states were governed by the [[List of tributaries of Imperial China|tributary]] system. Since the [[Emperor of China]] held the [[Mandate of Heaven]], his rule was universal and extended to [[Tianxia|All under heaven]]. Sometimes neighboring states were actual [[protectorate]]s or [[vassal state]]s over which China exerted large amounts of influence, while in other cases foreign states merely acknowledged China's nominal [[suzerainty]] in order to gain access to Chinese trade, which took place through the tributary system.<ref>{{cite book|author=Warren I. Cohen|title=East Asia at the Center: Four Thousand Years of Engagement with the World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Okjd2rDwb8IC&pg=PA28|year=2000|publisher=Columbia University Press|page=28|isbn=9780231502511}}</ref>\n\nThe king of the ancient [[Qin (state)|state of Qin]] first unified the Chinese empire in 221 BC by conquering all of the other states in what was then considered China and proclaimed himself the \"First Emperor\" and became known as [[Qin Shi Huang]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Spencer C. Tucker|title=A Global Chronology of Conflict: From the Ancient World to the Modern Middle East |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h5_tSnygvbIC&pg=PA419|year=2009|publisher=ABC-CLIO|page=419|isbn=9781851096725 }}</ref>\n\nThe ancient [[Han dynasty]] (202 BC \u2013 220 AD) established control over northern Vietnam, northern [[Korea]], and the [[Tarim Basin]] of Central Asia. The short-lived [[Sui dynasty]] (581\u2013618 AD) reinvaded [[Annam (Chinese Province)|Annam]] (northern Vietnam) and attacked [[Champa]] (southern Vietnam), while they also attempted to conquer [[Korea]], which failed (see [[Goguryeo-Sui Wars]]).<ref>{{cite book|author=Spencer C. Tucker|title=A Global Chronology of Conflict|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h5_tSnygvbIC&pg=108|year=2009|pages=108, 196|isbn=9781851096725}}</ref> \n\nThe later [[Tang dynasty]] (618\u2013907) aided the Korean [[Silla]] Kingdom in defeating their two Korean rivals, yet became shortchanged when they discovered Silla was not about to allow the Tang to claim much of [[Goguryeo]]'s territory (as it had been under the Chinese Han dynasty's control a few centuries before, the Han having wrested it from native kingdoms at that time). The Tang Dynasty established control over the Tarim Basin region as well, fighting wars with the new Tibetan Empire and stripping them of their colonies in Central Asia (which was abandoned after the [[An Lushan Rebellion]]). The [[Song dynasty]] (960\u20131279), in securing maritime trade routes that ran from South East Asia into the Indian Ocean, had established fortified trade bases in the Philippines. The Mongol-led [[Yuan dynasty]] (1279\u20131368) made attempts to invade [[Japan]] after securing the Korean peninsula through the vassaldom of the Korean [[Goryeo]] dynasty, yet both of these military ventures failed (see [[Mongol Invasions of Japan]]).<ref>{{cite book|author=James I. Matray|title=Crisis in a Divided Korea: A Chronology and Reference Guide: A Chronology and Reference Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QMLWCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA13|year=2016|publisher=ABC-CLIO|page=13|isbn=9781610699938}}</ref>\n\n==Qing territorial expansion==\n{{further|Ten Great Campaigns}}\nBy the late 19th century, in response to competition with other states, the [[Qing dynasty|Qing government]] of China attempted to exert direct control of its frontier areas by conquest or, if already under military control, conversion into provinces.\n\n[[Ming dynasty|Ming-dynasty]] loyalists from China invaded Taiwan and expelled Dutch colonialists from the island during the [[Siege of Fort Zeelandia]] and founded the Chinese [[Kingdom of Tungning]]. The Ming loyalists quickly moved to replace the institutions and culture of Dutch colonial rule with Han Chinese colonial rule. Language and religious institutions left by the Dutch were closed and replaced with Confucian temples and Chinese language schools for both Han Chinese and aboriginals. Officials encouraged new immigration of Han Chinese from China into territory further inland, turning aboriginal lands into new farmland.<ref>Wills J. Jr (2006), \"The Seventeenth Century Transformation\", in ''Taiwan: A New History'', Rubinstein, M. ed., M. E. Sharpe. {{ISBN|978-0-7656-1495-7}}.</ref> After fighting between the Ming loyalists and the [[Qing]] during the [[Revolt of the Three Feudatories]], the Qing attacked the Kingdom of Tungning. the Qing won the [[Battle of Penghu]] and the Ming loyalists submitted to Qing rule. Tungning was annexed as part of [[Fujian]] province. The Qing were \"reluctant colonizers\" but became convinced of Taiwan's value to their empire due to the threat the island posed if used as a base by rival powers, and by its abundant resources. <ref>Tonio Andrade, ''How Taiwan Became Chinese: Dutch, Spanish, and Han Colonization in the Seventeenth Century'', Columbia University Press.</ref> The Qing turned Taiwan into its own province in 1885, after [[Taiwan Expedition of 1874|Japanese interest]] and a defeated [[Keelung Campaign|French invasion]] attempt.\n\nAfter British troops [[British expedition to Tibet|invaded Tibet]] in the waning days of the Qing dynasty, the Qing responded by sending [[Zhao Erfeng]] to further integrate Tibet into China.  He succeeded in abolishing the powers of the Tibetan local leaders in [[Kham]] and appointing Chinese magistrates in their places by 1909\u201310. Qing forces were also sent to [[\u00dc-Tsang]] in 1910 to establish a direct control over Tibet proper, though a province was never established in this area.\n\n===Process of expansion===\nThe ability of Qing China to project power into [[Central Asia]] came about because of two changes, one social and one technological.  The social change was that under the Qing dynasty, from 1642, China came under the control of the [[Manchu people|Manchu]]s who organised their military forces around cavalry which was more suited for power projection than traditional Chinese infantry.  The technological change was advances in artillery which negated the military advantage that the people of the [[Steppe]] had with their cavalry. Zunghar Khanate (\u0417\u04af\u04af\u043d \u0433\u0430\u0440\u044b\u043d \u0445\u0430\u0430\u043d\u0442 \u0443\u043b\u0441) was the last great independent nomadic power on the steppe in Central Asia. The [[Dzungars]] were deliberately exterminated in a brutal campaign during the [[Zunghar Genocide]] by Manchu Bannermen and Khalkha Mongols. It has been estimated that more than a million people were slaughtered, and it took generations for it to recover.<ref>Christian Tyler, ''Wild West China: The Taming of Xinjiang'' (Rutgers UP, 2003) p. 55</ref>  The Manchu ruling family ([[Aisin Gioro]]) was a supporter of Tibetan Buddhism and so many of the ruling groups were linked by religion.\n\n===Burma (Myanmar) === \nThe Qing campaign against Burma (Myanmar) (1765-70) was its most disastrous and costly frontier war. It ended in a stalemate but the Qing rulers could not accept Burma as an equal, and when diplomatic relations were resumed in 1790, the Qing court considered it a restoration of Chinese suzerainty.<ref>Yingcong Dai, \"A disguised defeat: The Myanmar campaign of the Qing dynasty.\" ''Modern Asian Studies'' 38.1 (2004): 145-189.</ref>\n\n==Recent tensions ==\n{{Further|East China Sea EEZ disputes|Belt and Road Initiative}}\nWith the 1978 [[Chinese economic reform]] launched by [[Deng Xiaoping]], China has increased its political stance, its influence and its power abroad.<ref>{{cite book|author=Asle Toje|title=Will China's Rise Be Peaceful?: Security, Stability, and Legitimacy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vA5EDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT24|year=2017|publisher=Oxford University Press|pages=24\u201325|isbn=9780190675417}}</ref> On one side, China remains deeply neutral and not involving in any conflict, and the land borders are stable.  China has increased its influence, while using military and economic wealth and claims to island territories that have caused anxiety in neighbors to the east, such as the Philippines and Japan. <ref>Humphrey Hawksley, ''Asian Waters: The Struggle Over the South China Sea and the Strategy of Chinese Expansion'' (2018)</ref><ref>See  [https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2016/07/13/asia-pacific/china-blames-philippines-stirring-trouble-inherent-territory/  \"Beijing says it could declare ADIZ over South China Sea\"  ''The Japan Times''  July 13, 2016] </ref>\nJeffrey  Reeves (2018),  argues that since 2012 the Xi administration has demonstrated \"a concerted imperialist policy\" towards its developing neighbor states to the south and west, especially [[Mongolia-China relations|Mongolia]],<ref> Jeffrey Reeves,  \"Rethinking weak state behavior: Mongolia\u2019s foreign policy toward China.\" ''International Politics'' 51.2 (2014): 254-271.</ref> [[Kazakhstan-China relations|Kazakhstan]], [[Tajikistan-China relations|Tajikistan]], [[Kyrgyzstan-China relations|Kyrgyzstan]], [[Afghanistan-China relations|Afghanistan]], [[Pakistan-China relations|Pakistan]], [[Nepal-China relations|Nepal]], [[Myanmar-China relations|Myanmar]], [[Cambodia-China relations|Cambodia]], [[Laos-China relations|Laos]] and [[Vietnam-China relations|Vietnam]]. <ref>Jeffrey Reeves,  \"Imperialism and the Middle Kingdom: the Xi Jinping administration\u2019s peripheral diplomacy with developing states.\" ''Third World Quarterly'' 39.5 (2018): 976-998.</ref>\nChinese overseas populations are also said to play a disproportionate role in Southeast Asian economies in what is referred to as the [[bamboo network]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|China}}\n* [[History of China]]\n* [[Monarchy of China]]\n* [[Chinese nationalism]]\n* [[Emperor at home, king abroad]]\n* [[Sinicization]]\n* [[Sinocentrism]]\n* [[Tributary system of China]]\n* [[Territorial disputes in the South China Sea]]\n* [[Western imperialism in Asia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Library resources box}}\n* Chan, Steve. ''China's Troubled Waters: Maritime Disputes in Theoretical Perspective'' (Cambridge UP, 2016) [https://www.amazon.com/Chinas-Troubled-Waters-Theoretical-Perspective/dp/1107573297/  excerpt]\n* Chang, Chun-shu. ''The Rise of the Chinese Empire: Nation, State, and Imperialism in Early China, ca. 1600 B.C.\u2013A.D. 8'' (Volume 1,  University of Michigan Press, 2007).\n* {{cite book|author=Cohen, Warren I. |title=East Asia at the Center: Four Thousand Years of Engagement with the World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Okjd2rDwb8IC&pg=PA28|year=2000|publisher=Columbia University Press|page=passim|isbn=9780231502511}}\n* Hawksley, Humphrey. ''Asian Waters: The Struggle Over the South China Sea and the Strategy of Chinese Expansion'' (2018) [https://www.amazon.com/Asian-Waters-Struggle-Strategy-Expansion-ebook/dp/B07MXDFQK1/ excerpt]\n* Mancall, Mark. ''China at the Center: 300 Years of Foreign Policy'' (1984)\n* Reeves, Jeffrey.  \"Imperialism and the Middle Kingdom: the Xi Jinping administration\u2019s peripheral diplomacy with developing states.\" ''Third World Quarterly'' 39.5 (2018): 976-998. \n* Setzekorn, Eric. \"Chinese Imperialism, Ethnic Cleansing, and Military History, 1850-1877.\" ''Journal of Chinese Military History'' 4.1 (2015): 80-100.\n* {{cite book|author=Tucker, Spencer C. |title=A Global Chronology of Conflict: From the Ancient World to the Modern Middle East &#91;|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h5_tSnygvbIC&pg=PA419|date= 2009|publisher=ABC-CLIO|page=passim|isbn=9781851096725}}\n* Toje, Asle. ''Will China's Rise Be Peaceful?: Security, Stability, and Legitimacy'' (Oxford UP,   2017). [https://www.amazon.com/Will-Chinas-Rise-Peaceful-Legitimacy/dp/019067539X/ excerpt]\n* Westad, Odd Arne. ''Restless Empire: China and the World Since 1750'' (2012) [https://www.amazon.com/Restless-Empire-China-World-Since/dp/0465056679/ excerpt]\n\n[[Category:Imperialism]]\n[[Category:Imperial China]]\n[[Category:History of China]]\n", "text_old": "Over the last four thousand years Chinese [[imperialism]] and expansion has been a central feature of the history of East Asia. Since the recovery of Chinese strength in the late 20th century, the issues involved have been of concern to China's neighbors to the east.\n\n==Early Chinese expansions==\nIn Chinese political theory, relations between foreign states were governed by the [[List of tributaries of Imperial China|tributary]] system. Since the [[Emperor of China]] held the [[Mandate of Heaven]], his rule was universal and extended to [[Tianxia|All under heaven]]. Sometimes neighboring states were actual [[protectorate]]s or [[vassal state]]s over which China exerted large amounts of influence, while in other cases foreign states merely acknowledged China's nominal [[suzerainty]] in order to gain access to Chinese trade, which took place through the tributary system.<ref>{{cite book|author=Warren I. Cohen|title=East Asia at the Center: Four Thousand Years of Engagement with the World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Okjd2rDwb8IC&pg=PA28|year=2000|publisher=Columbia University Press|page=28|isbn=9780231502511}}</ref>\n\nThe king of the ancient [[Qin (state)|state of Qin]] first unified the Chinese empire in 221 BC by conquering all of the other states in what was then considered China and proclaimed himself the \"First Emperor\" and became known as [[Qin Shi Huang]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Spencer C. Tucker|title=A Global Chronology of Conflict: From the Ancient World to the Modern Middle East |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h5_tSnygvbIC&pg=PA419|year=2009|publisher=ABC-CLIO|page=419|isbn=9781851096725 }}</ref>\n\nThe ancient [[Han dynasty]] (202 BC \u2013 220 AD) established control over northern Vietnam, northern [[Korea]], and the [[Tarim Basin]] of Central Asia. The short-lived [[Sui dynasty]] (581\u2013618 AD) reinvaded [[Annam (Chinese Province)|Annam]] (northern Vietnam) and attacked [[Champa]] (southern Vietnam), while they also attempted to conquer [[Korea]], which failed (see [[Goguryeo-Sui Wars]]).<ref>{{cite book|author=Spencer C. Tucker|title=A Global Chronology of Conflict|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h5_tSnygvbIC&pg=108|year=2009|pages=108, 196|isbn=9781851096725}}</ref> \n\nThe later [[Tang dynasty]] (618\u2013907) aided the Korean [[Silla]] Kingdom in defeating their two Korean rivals, yet became shortchanged when they discovered Silla was not about to allow the Tang to claim much of [[Goguryeo]]'s territory (as it had been under the Chinese Han dynasty's control a few centuries before, the Han having wrested it from native kingdoms at that time). The Tang Dynasty established control over the Tarim Basin region as well, fighting wars with the new Tibetan Empire and stripping them of their colonies in Central Asia (which was abandoned after the [[An Lushan Rebellion]]). The [[Song dynasty]] (960\u20131279), in securing maritime trade routes that ran from South East Asia into the Indian Ocean, had established fortified trade bases in the Philippines. The Mongol-led [[Yuan dynasty]] (1279\u20131368) made attempts to invade [[Japan]] after securing the Korean peninsula through the vassaldom of the Korean [[Goryeo]] dynasty, yet both of these military ventures failed (see [[Mongol Invasions of Japan]]).<ref>{{cite book|author=James I. Matray|title=Crisis in a Divided Korea: A Chronology and Reference Guide: A Chronology and Reference Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QMLWCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA13|year=2016|publisher=ABC-CLIO|page=13|isbn=9781610699938}}</ref>\n\n==Qing territorial expansion==\n{{further|Ten Great Campaigns}}\nBy the late 19th century, in response to competition with other states, the [[Qing dynasty|Qing government]] of China attempted to exert direct control of its frontier areas by conquest or, if already under military control, conversion into provinces.\n\n[[Ming dynasty|Ming-dynasty]] loyalists from China invaded Taiwan and expelled Dutch colonialists from the island during the [[Siege of Fort Zeelandia]] and founded the Chinese [[Kingdom of Tungning]]. The Ming loyalists quickly moved to replace the institutions and culture of Dutch colonial rule with Han Chinese colonial rule. Language and religious institutions left by the Dutch were closed and replaced with Confucian temples and Chinese language schools for both Han Chinese and aboriginals. Officials encouraged new immigration of Han Chinese from China into territory further inland, turning aboriginal lands into new farmland.<ref>Wills J. Jr (2006), \"The Seventeenth Century Transformation\", in ''Taiwan: A New History'', Rubinstein, M. ed., M. E. Sharpe. {{ISBN|978-0-7656-1495-7}}.</ref> After fighting between the Ming loyalists and the [[Qing]] during the [[Revolt of the Three Feudatories]], the Qing attacked the Kingdom of Tungning. the Qing won the [[Battle of Penghu]] and the Ming loyalists submitted to Qing rule. Tungning was annexed as part of [[Fujian]] province. The Qing were \"reluctant colonizers\" but became convinced of Taiwan's value to their empire due to the threat the island posed if used as a base by rival powers, and by its abundant resources. <ref>Tonio Andrade, ''How Taiwan Became Chinese: Dutch, Spanish, and Han Colonization in the Seventeenth Century'', Columbia University Press.</ref> The Qing turned Taiwan into its own province in 1885, after [[Taiwan Expedition of 1874|Japanese interest]] and a defeated [[Keelung Campaign|French invasion]] attempt.\n\nAfter British troops [[British expedition to Tibet|invaded Tibet]] in the waning days of the Qing dynasty, the Qing responded by sending [[Zhao Erfeng]] to further integrate Tibet into China.  He succeeded in abolishing the powers of the Tibetan local leaders in [[Kham]] and appointing Chinese magistrates in their places by 1909\u201310. Qing forces were also sent to [[\u00dc-Tsang]] in 1910 to establish a direct control over Tibet proper, though a province was never established in this area.\n\n===Process of expansion===\nThe ability of Qing China to project power into [[Central Asia]] came about because of two changes, one social and one technological.  The social change was that under the Qing dynasty, from 1642, China came under the control of the [[Manchu people|Manchu]]s who organised their military forces around cavalry which was more suited for power projection than traditional Chinese infantry.  The technological change was advances in artillery which negated the military advantage that the people of the [[Steppe]] had with their cavalry. Zunghar Khanate (\u0417\u04af\u04af\u043d \u0433\u0430\u0440\u044b\u043d \u0445\u0430\u0430\u043d\u0442 \u0443\u043b\u0441) was the last great independent nomadic power on the steppe in Central Asia. The [[Dzungars]] were deliberately exterminated in a brutal campaign during the [[Zunghar Genocide]] by Manchu Bannermen and Khalkha Mongols. It has been estimated that more than a million people were slaughtered, and it took generations for it to recover.<ref>Christian Tyler, ''Wild West China: The Taming of Xinjiang'' (Rutgers UP, 2003) p. 55</ref>  The Manchu ruling family ([[Aisin Gioro]]) was a supporter of Tibetan Buddhism and so many of the ruling groups were linked by religion.\n\n===Burma (Myanmar) === \nThe Qing campaign against Burma (Myanmar) (1765-70) was its most disastrous and costly frontier war. It ended in a stalemate but the Qing rulers could not accept Burma as an equal, and when diplomatic relations were resumed in 1790, the Qing court considered this was a restoration of Chinese suzerainty.<ref>Yingcong Dai, \"A disguised defeat: The Myanmar campaign of the Qing dynasty.\" ''Modern Asian Studies'' 38.1 (2004): 145-189.</ref>\n\n==Recent tensions ==\n{{Further|East China Sea EEZ disputes|Belt and Road Initiative}}\nWith the 1978 [[Chinese economic reform]] launched by [[Deng Xiaoping]], China has increased its political stance, its influence and its power abroad.<ref>{{cite book|author=Asle Toje|title=Will China's Rise Be Peaceful?: Security, Stability, and Legitimacy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vA5EDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT24|year=2017|publisher=Oxford University Press|pages=24\u201325|isbn=9780190675417}}</ref> On one side, China remains deeply neutral and not involving in any conflict, and the land borders are stable.  China has increased its influence, while using military and economic wealth and claims to island territories that have caused anxiety in neighbors to the east, such as the Philippines and Japan. <ref>Humphrey Hawksley, ''Asian Waters: The Struggle Over the South China Sea and the Strategy of Chinese Expansion'' (2018)</ref><ref>See  [https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2016/07/13/asia-pacific/china-blames-philippines-stirring-trouble-inherent-territory/  \"Beijing says it could declare ADIZ over South China Sea\"  ''The Japan Times''  July 13, 2016] </ref>\nJeffrey  Reeves (2018),  argues that since 2012 the Xi administration has demonstrated \"a concerted imperialist policy\" towards its developing neighbor states to the south and west, especially [[Mongolia-China relations|Mongolia]],<ref> Jeffrey Reeves,  \"Rethinking weak state behavior: Mongolia\u2019s foreign policy toward China.\" ''International Politics'' 51.2 (2014): 254-271.</ref> [[Kazakhstan-China relations|Kazakhstan]], [[Tajikistan-China relations|Tajikistan]], [[Kyrgyzstan-China relations|Kyrgyzstan]], [[Afghanistan-China relations|Afghanistan]], [[Pakistan-China relations|Pakistan]], [[Nepal-China relations|Nepal]], [[Myanmar-China relations|Myanmar]], [[Cambodia-China relations|Cambodia]], [[Laos-China relations|Laos]] and [[Vietnam-China relations|Vietnam]]. <ref>Jeffrey Reeves,  \"Imperialism and the Middle Kingdom: the Xi Jinping administration\u2019s peripheral diplomacy with developing states.\" ''Third World Quarterly'' 39.5 (2018): 976-998.</ref>\nChinese overseas populations are also said to play a disproportionate role in Southeast Asian economies in what is referred to as the [[bamboo network]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|China}}\n* [[History of China]]\n* [[Monarchy of China]]\n* [[Chinese nationalism]]\n* [[Emperor at home, king abroad]]\n* [[Sinicization]]\n* [[Sinocentrism]]\n* [[Tributary system of China]]\n* [[Territorial disputes in the South China Sea]]\n* [[Western imperialism in Asia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Library resources box}}\n* Chan, Steve. ''China's Troubled Waters: Maritime Disputes in Theoretical Perspective'' (Cambridge UP, 2016) [https://www.amazon.com/Chinas-Troubled-Waters-Theoretical-Perspective/dp/1107573297/  excerpt]\n* Chang, Chun-shu. ''The Rise of the Chinese Empire: Nation, State, and Imperialism in Early China, ca. 1600 B.C.\u2013A.D. 8'' (Volume 1,  University of Michigan Press, 2007).\n* {{cite book|author=Cohen, Warren I. |title=East Asia at the Center: Four Thousand Years of Engagement with the World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Okjd2rDwb8IC&pg=PA28|year=2000|publisher=Columbia University Press|page=passim|isbn=9780231502511}}\n* Hawksley, Humphrey. ''Asian Waters: The Struggle Over the South China Sea and the Strategy of Chinese Expansion'' (2018) [https://www.amazon.com/Asian-Waters-Struggle-Strategy-Expansion-ebook/dp/B07MXDFQK1/ excerpt]\n* Mancall, Mark. ''China at the Center: 300 Years of Foreign Policy'' (1984)\n* Reeves, Jeffrey.  \"Imperialism and the Middle Kingdom: the Xi Jinping administration\u2019s peripheral diplomacy with developing states.\" ''Third World Quarterly'' 39.5 (2018): 976-998. \n* Setzekorn, Eric. \"Chinese Imperialism, Ethnic Cleansing, and Military History, 1850-1877.\" ''Journal of Chinese Military History'' 4.1 (2015): 80-100.\n* {{cite book|author=Tucker, Spencer C. |title=A Global Chronology of Conflict: From the Ancient World to the Modern Middle East &#91;|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h5_tSnygvbIC&pg=PA419|date= 2009|publisher=ABC-CLIO|page=passim|isbn=9781851096725}}\n* Toje, Asle. ''Will China's Rise Be Peaceful?: Security, Stability, and Legitimacy'' (Oxford UP,   2017). [https://www.amazon.com/Will-Chinas-Rise-Peaceful-Legitimacy/dp/019067539X/ excerpt]\n* Westad, Odd Arne. ''Restless Empire: China and the World Since 1750'' (2012) [https://www.amazon.com/Restless-Empire-China-World-Since/dp/0465056679/ excerpt]\n\n[[Category:Imperialism]]\n[[Category:Imperial China]]\n[[Category:History of China]]\n", "name_user": "Subowei.sully", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_imperialism"}
{"title_page": "LGBT culture in Singapore", "text_new": "{{See also|LGBT rights in Singapore}}\n{{Use Singapore English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Refimprove|date=June 2011}}\n\n{{Life in Singapore}}\nThere are no statistics on how many LGBT people there are in Singapore or what percentage of the population they constitute. [[Section 377A of the Penal Code (Singapore)|Section 377A of the Penal Code]] criminalises sexual acts between men, including consensual, public and private activities. Men found guilty can be jailed for up to two years.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-52098362</ref> Sexual acts between women are currently legal.\n\n==Notable residents identifying as LGBT==\n===Historical===\n====Paddy Chew====\n{{Main|Paddy Chew}}\nChew was the first Singaporean to publicly declare his [[HIV]]-positive status. He came out on 12 December 1998 during the [[First National AIDS Conference in Singapore]]. He identified his orientation as [[bisexuality|bisexual]]. His affliction was dramatised in a play called \"[[Completely With/Out Character]]\" produced by [[The Necessary Stage]], directed by [[Alvin Tan]] and written by [[Haresh Sharma]], staged from 10\u201317 May 1999. He died on 21 August 1999, shortly after the play's run ended.\n\n====Arthur Yap====\n{{Main|Arthur Yap}}\nYap was a poet who won the 1983 Singapore Cultural Medallion for Literature. He died of laryngeal carcinoma on 19 June 2006, bequeathing $500,000/-, part of his estate which included his apartment off Killiney Road, to the National Cancer Centre Singapore (NCSS) where he was a patient.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.todayonline.com/articles/264684.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-07-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080713044107/http://www.todayonline.com/articles/264684.asp |archivedate=13 July 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Arts personalities===\n* [[Cyril Wong]], poet.\n* [[Alfian Sa'at]], writer, poet and playwright. He had a weekly column on gay website [[Trevvy]] titled, \"Iced Bandung\".\n* [[Ng Yi-Sheng]], writer and performance artist. Ng is the author of a collection of personally written poems including gay-themed ones.\n* [[B]], fashion designer, stylist & entertainer.\n\n===Politicians===\n* [[Vincent Wijeysingha]]; Wijeysingha became the first Singaporean politician to openly declare that he was gay when he made a post on Facebook ahead of the annual Pink Dot SG event.<ref>[http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/vincent-wijeysingha-becomes-first-politician-come-out-singapore290613]</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\n==== Leon Markcus  ====\nLeon Markcus is a [[Singer-songwriter|singer/songwriter]] who has publicly spoken about their support for queer rights in [[Asia]]. Most notably, through their music video 'Circles (feat. Sherlyn Veronica, THIEVVES) [2017]'  as well as lending their support by performing over at [[Pink Dot SG|Pink dot]] Hong Kong in 2017, Hong Kong & Taiwan Pride 2018. They identify as a [[Genderqueer|non-binary]] [[bisexuality|bisexual]]. Apart from advocating for queer youths,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://instinctmagazine.com/post/singapore-singer-leon-markcus-standing-lgbtq-youth|title=Singapore Singer Leon Markcus's Standing Up For LGBTQ Kids|date=2017-10-26|work=Instinct|access-date=2018-04-29|language=en}}</ref> Markcus, also advocates for body positivity as well as mental health awareness.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/health-beauty/article/2118871/singapore-star-leon-markcus-opens-anorexia-while-hongkongers|title=Singapore star Leon Markcus opens up on his eating disorder|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=2018-04-29|language=en}}</ref> Their notable songs include 'Alive' (2017) and their E.P 'Mannequin' (2016).\n\n'''Jean Seizure'''\nJean Seizure is a singer/songwriter, spoken word artist and actress. Her song and music video 'Night' offers a glimpse into how it's like to be in an underground, queer relationship in Singapore, and the toxic circumstances surrounding it that eventually takes a toll on the people in the relationship. [2018] She has performed at Pink dot in 2017 with her a cappella band, The Apex Project, another Singaporean group that is notable for incorporating LGBT representation in their songs and music videos.\n\n==Cyberspace==\nSingapore has particularly established [[LGBT]] portals owing to its high Internet penetration rates and the restriction on LGBT content in print and broadcast media.\n\n*[[Blowing Wind Gay Forum]]  is an online discussion forum for gay men in Singapore started in 1997 to discuss any issues which concern them. It eschews political, religious, and anti-racial topics.\n*[[Fridae.asia]] is Asia's largest English-language LGBT portal.\n*[[Gay SG Confessions]], also known as 'GSC' - Started in February 2013 in the footsteps of a host of popular \"confessions\" websites, GSC is a [[Facebook]] page that hosts a collection of user-contributed stories by gay, bisexual, lesbian, straight, transgender and curious members. The page was a sleeper published over 500 'confessions' or posts within less than 2 weeks of its creation<ref>Gay Star News [http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/singapore-gay-men-jump-chance-confess-secrets270213 \"Singapore Gay Men Jump At Chance To Confess Secrets\"], ''[[Gay Star News]]'', 27 February 2013. Retrieved on 11 October 2013.</ref> and garnering over 10,000 page 'Likes' in slightly over 6 months. The site is run by an anonymous moderator, an account director in an advertising firm in his 30s who wants to be known only as \"GC\".<ref>Asia One News [http://news.asiaone.com/News/Latest+News/Science+and+Tech/Story/A1Story20130318-409443.html \"Many 'like' to confess online\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111093439/http://news.asiaone.com/News/Latest+News/Science+and+Tech/Story/A1Story20130318-409443.html |date=11 November 2013 }} \"[[AsiaOne]]\", 19 March 2013, para 14. Retrieved on 11 October 2013.</ref>\n*[[Lesbian SG Confessions]], started in February 2013, is a similar Facebook page to [[Gay SG Confessions]] that publishes 'confessions' anonymously.\n*[[Trevvy]], formerly known as SgBoy - was set up in March 1999, originally known as \"Singapore Boy Homepage\" before being renamed SgBoy. It is one of the most popular LGBT portals in Singapore. It underwent a makeover, rebranding itself as Trevvy.com in August 2006, shifting its focus to the more mature 25 to 40-year age group of the local gay market and expanding its user base regionally.\n\n==Organisations supporting LGBT rights==\n* [[Free Community Church|The Free Community Church]]\n* [[Pelangi Pride Centre]] (PPC), Singapore's first LGBT Centre\n\n==Arts venues==\nThe following list consists of exhibition and performance venues where many works dealing with LGBT themes or by LGBT arts practitioners have been held. However, they are not exclusively used for such purposes.\n* [[The Substation]], founded in 1990 by the late [[Kuo Pao Kun]], is Singapore's first independent contemporary arts centre, centrally located in the [[civic district]]. Its sub-sections include a [[black box theater]], a gallery, a dance studio, the Blue Room<!--LINK IS DAB--> and two multi-function classrooms. It was the venue for the nascent [[People Like Us (Singapore)|PLU]] Sunday meetings in the early 90s. The historic [[PLU 2]] pre-registration discussion was also held in the Blue Room<!--LINK IS DAB--> in 2003.\n* Utterly Art provides exhibition space and management services to local and Asian artists, and photographers. [[Contra/Diction-A Night with Gay Poets]], Singapore's first public gay poetry reading session, was held on 4 August 2005.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|LGBT|Singapore}}\n* [[LGBT history in Singapore]]\n* [[Human male sexuality]]\n* [[Pink Dot SG]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links and references==\n{{Commons category|LGBT in Singapore}}\n* [https://www.blowingwind.io/forum/index.php Blowing Wind Gay Forum]\n* The [[Yawning Bread]] website: [http://yawningbread.wordpress.com/],[https://web.archive.org/web/20050405224059/http://www.yawningbread.org/index2.htm]\n* [[Trevvy]] (formerly [[SGBOY]]): [http://www.trevvy.com/]\n* [[Gay SG Confessions]]: [http://www.fb.com/GaySGconfessions/]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/Les.SgConfessions Lesbian SG Confessions]\n* [[Fridae.com]]: [http://www.fridae.com/index.php?6708&&notlogin]\n* [http://www.singapore-gay.com Gay Singapore Guide]\n* [[Utopia (website)|Utopia]]'s Singapore listings: [http://www.utopia-asia.com/tipssing.htm]\n* An archive of local and international LGBT-related video and newsclips shown on Singapore television on [[YouTube]]: [https://www.youtube.com/view_play_list?p=E024DF324928BFDC] and [[Google Video]]: [http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=-6415708530651271619], and video recordings of LGBT events held in Singapore: [https://www.youtube.com/view_play_list?p=B8A7F3D4B67630E5].\n* Profusely illustrated original versions and backups of deleted Wikipedia articles regarding Singaporean LGBT culture on [[SgWiki]]: [http://www.sgwiki.com/wiki/Homosexuality_in_Singapore]\n* [[The Purple Alliance]]: [http://www.thepurplealliance.org/] \n* [[Sayoni]]: [http://www.sayoni.com/] - Singapore-based organisation for Asian queer women\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071120103008/http://www.sgwiki.com/wiki/Singapore_sexual_slang Singapore sexual slang]\n* [[Lee Kuan Yew]]'s views on homosexuality: [http://www.sgwiki.com/wiki/Lee_Kuan_Yew%27s_views_on_homosexuality]\n* [http://www.eoc.org.hk/EOC/Upload/UserFiles/File/LGBT.pdf Creating Inclusive Workplaces for LGBT Employees]\n{{Homosexuality around the world}}\n{{LGBTcultureworldwide}}\n{{SingaporeLGBTTopics}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}\n\n[[Category:LGBT in Singapore]]\n", "text_old": "{{See also|LGBT rights in Singapore}}\n{{Use Singapore English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Refimprove|date=June 2011}}\n\n{{Life in Singapore}}\nThere are no statistics on how many LGBT people there are in Singapore or what percentage of the population they constitute. [[Section 377A of the Penal Code (Singapore)|Section 377A of the Penal Code]] criminalises sexual acts between men, including consensual and private activities, though it's unenforced. Sexual acts between women are legal.\n\n==Notable residents identifying as LGBT==\n\n===Historical===\n\n====Paddy Chew====\n{{Main|Paddy Chew}}\nChew was the first Singaporean to publicly declare his [[HIV]]-positive status. He came out on 12 December 1998 during the [[First National AIDS Conference in Singapore]]. He identified his orientation as [[bisexuality|bisexual]]. His affliction was dramatised in a play called \"[[Completely With/Out Character]]\" produced by [[The Necessary Stage]], directed by [[Alvin Tan]] and written by [[Haresh Sharma]], staged from 10\u201317 May 1999. He died on 21 August 1999, shortly after the play's run ended.\n\n====Arthur Yap====\n{{Main|Arthur Yap}}\nYap was a poet who won the 1983 Singapore Cultural Medallion for Literature. He died of laryngeal carcinoma on 19 June 2006, bequeathing $500,000/-, part of his estate which included his apartment off Killiney Road, to the National Cancer Centre Singapore (NCSS) where he was a patient.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.todayonline.com/articles/264684.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-07-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080713044107/http://www.todayonline.com/articles/264684.asp |archivedate=13 July 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Arts personalities===\n* [[Cyril Wong]], poet.\n* [[Alfian Sa'at]], writer, poet and playwright. He had a weekly column on gay website [[Trevvy]] titled, \"Iced Bandung\".\n* [[Ng Yi-Sheng]], writer and performance artist. Ng is the author of a collection of personally written poems including gay-themed ones.\n* [[B]], fashion designer, stylist & entertainer.\n\n===Politicians===\n* [[Vincent Wijeysingha]]; Wijeysingha became the first Singaporean politician to openly declare that he was gay when he made a post on Facebook ahead of the annual Pink Dot SG event.<ref>[http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/vincent-wijeysingha-becomes-first-politician-come-out-singapore290613]</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\n\n==== Leon Markcus  ====\nLeon Markcus is a [[Singer-songwriter|singer/songwriter]] who has publicly spoken about their support for queer rights in [[Asia]]. Most notably, through their music video 'Circles (feat. Sherlyn Veronica, THIEVVES) [2017]'  as well as lending their support by performing over at [[Pink Dot SG|Pink dot]] Hong Kong in 2017, Hong Kong & Taiwan Pride 2018. They identify as a [[Genderqueer|non-binary]] [[bisexuality|bisexual]]. Apart from advocating for queer youths,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://instinctmagazine.com/post/singapore-singer-leon-markcus-standing-lgbtq-youth|title=Singapore Singer Leon Markcus's Standing Up For LGBTQ Kids|date=2017-10-26|work=Instinct|access-date=2018-04-29|language=en}}</ref> Markcus, also advocates for body positivity as well as mental health awareness.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/health-beauty/article/2118871/singapore-star-leon-markcus-opens-anorexia-while-hongkongers|title=Singapore star Leon Markcus opens up on his eating disorder|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=2018-04-29|language=en}}</ref> Their notable songs include 'Alive' (2017) and their E.P 'Mannequin' (2016).\n\n'''Jean Seizure'''\n\nJean Seizure is a singer/songwriter, spoken word artist and actress. Her song and music video 'Night' offers a glimpse into how it's like to be in an underground, queer relationship in Singapore, and the toxic circumstances surrounding it that eventually takes a toll on the people in the relationship. [2018] She has performed at Pink dot in 2017 with her a cappella band, The Apex Project, another Singaporean group that is notable for incorporating LGBT representation in their songs and music videos.\n\n==Cyberspace==\n\nSingapore has particularly established [[LGBT]] portals owing to its high Internet penetration rates and the restriction on LGBT content in print and broadcast media.\n\n*[[Blowing Wind Gay Forum]]  is an online discussion forum for gay men in Singapore started in 1997 to discuss any issues which concern them. It eschews political, religious, and anti-racial topics.\n*[[Fridae.asia]] is Asia's largest English-language LGBT portal.\n*[[Gay SG Confessions]], also known as 'GSC' - Started in February 2013 in the footsteps of a host of popular \"confessions\" websites, GSC is a [[Facebook]] page that hosts a collection of user-contributed stories by gay, bisexual, lesbian, straight, transgender and curious members. The page was a sleeper published over 500 'confessions' or posts within less than 2 weeks of its creation<ref>Gay Star News [http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/singapore-gay-men-jump-chance-confess-secrets270213 \"Singapore Gay Men Jump At Chance To Confess Secrets\"], ''[[Gay Star News]]'', 27 February 2013. Retrieved on 11 October 2013.</ref> and garnering over 10,000 page 'Likes' in slightly over 6 months. The site is run by an anonymous moderator, an account director in an advertising firm in his 30s who wants to be known only as \"GC\".<ref>Asia One News [http://news.asiaone.com/News/Latest+News/Science+and+Tech/Story/A1Story20130318-409443.html \"Many 'like' to confess online\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111093439/http://news.asiaone.com/News/Latest+News/Science+and+Tech/Story/A1Story20130318-409443.html |date=11 November 2013 }} \"[[AsiaOne]]\", 19 March 2013, para 14. Retrieved on 11 October 2013.</ref>\n*[[Lesbian SG Confessions]], started in February 2013, is a similar Facebook page to [[Gay SG Confessions]] that publishes 'confessions' anonymously.\n*[[Trevvy]], formerly known as SgBoy - was set up in March 1999, originally known as \"Singapore Boy Homepage\" before being renamed SgBoy. It is one of the most popular LGBT portals in Singapore. It underwent a makeover, rebranding itself as Trevvy.com in August 2006, shifting its focus to the more mature 25 to 40-year age group of the local gay market and expanding its user base regionally.\n\n==Organisations supporting LGBT rights==\n* [[Free Community Church|The Free Community Church]]\n* [[Pelangi Pride Centre]] (PPC), Singapore's first LGBT Centre\n\n==Arts venues==\nThe following list consists of exhibition and performance venues where many works dealing with LGBT themes or by LGBT arts practitioners have been held. However, they are not exclusively used for such purposes.\n* [[The Substation]], founded in 1990 by the late [[Kuo Pao Kun]], is Singapore's first independent contemporary arts centre, centrally located in the [[civic district]]. Its sub-sections include a [[black box theater]], a gallery, a dance studio, the Blue Room<!--LINK IS DAB--> and two multi-function classrooms. It was the venue for the nascent [[People Like Us (Singapore)|PLU]] Sunday meetings in the early 90s. The historic [[PLU 2]] pre-registration discussion was also held in the Blue Room<!--LINK IS DAB--> in 2003.\n* Utterly Art provides exhibition space and management services to local and Asian artists, and photographers. [[Contra/Diction-A Night with Gay Poets]], Singapore's first public gay poetry reading session, was held on 4 August 2005.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|LGBT|Singapore}}\n* [[LGBT history in Singapore]]\n* [[Human male sexuality]]\n* [[Pink Dot SG]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links and references==\n{{Commons category|LGBT in Singapore}}\n* [https://www.blowingwind.io/forum/index.php Blowing Wind Gay Forum]\n* The [[Yawning Bread]] website: [http://yawningbread.wordpress.com/],[https://web.archive.org/web/20050405224059/http://www.yawningbread.org/index2.htm]\n* [[Trevvy]] (formerly [[SGBOY]]): [http://www.trevvy.com/]\n* [[Gay SG Confessions]]: [http://www.fb.com/GaySGconfessions/]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/Les.SgConfessions Lesbian SG Confessions]\n* [[Fridae.com]]: [http://www.fridae.com/index.php?6708&&notlogin]\n* [http://www.singapore-gay.com Gay Singapore Guide]\n* [[Utopia (website)|Utopia]]'s Singapore listings: [http://www.utopia-asia.com/tipssing.htm]\n* An archive of local and international LGBT-related video and newsclips shown on Singapore television on [[YouTube]]: [https://www.youtube.com/view_play_list?p=E024DF324928BFDC] and [[Google Video]]: [http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=-6415708530651271619], and video recordings of LGBT events held in Singapore: [https://www.youtube.com/view_play_list?p=B8A7F3D4B67630E5].\n* Profusely illustrated original versions and backups of deleted Wikipedia articles regarding Singaporean LGBT culture on [[SgWiki]]: [http://www.sgwiki.com/wiki/Homosexuality_in_Singapore]\n* [[The Purple Alliance]]: [http://www.thepurplealliance.org/] \n* [[Sayoni]]: [http://www.sayoni.com/] - Singapore-based organisation for Asian queer women\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071120103008/http://www.sgwiki.com/wiki/Singapore_sexual_slang Singapore sexual slang]\n* [[Lee Kuan Yew]]'s views on homosexuality: [http://www.sgwiki.com/wiki/Lee_Kuan_Yew%27s_views_on_homosexuality]\n* [http://www.eoc.org.hk/EOC/Upload/UserFiles/File/LGBT.pdf Creating Inclusive Workplaces for LGBT Employees]\n{{Homosexuality around the world}}\n{{LGBTcultureworldwide}}\n{{SingaporeLGBTTopics}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}\n\n[[Category:LGBT in Singapore]]\n", "name_user": "BabsEverAfter", "label": "safe", "comment": "revert edit of sick, homophobe Favonian (well known troll) - as per previous comments on this and other articles.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LGBT_culture_in_Singapore"}
{"title_page": "Siheung", "text_new": "{{about|a city in Gyeonggi-do|a ''dong'' in Geumcheon-gu|Siheung-dong|others|Siheung (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = {{raise|0.1em|Siheung}}\n| native_name                     = {{lower|0.1em|{{lang|ko-Hang|\uc2dc\ud765\uc2dc}}}}\n| translit_lang1                  = Korean\n| settlement_type                 = [[Cities of South Korea|Municipal City]]\n| translit_lang1_type1            = [[Hangul]]\n| translit_lang1_info1            = {{lang|ko-Hang|{{linktext|\uc2dc|\ud765|\uc2dc}}}}\n| translit_lang1_type2            = [[Hanja]]\n| translit_lang1_info2            = {{lang|ko-Hant|{{linktext|\u59cb|\u8208|\u5e02}}}}\n| translit_lang1_type3            = {{nowrap|Revised Romanization}}\n| translit_lang1_info3            = Siheung-si\n| translit_lang1_type4            = {{nowrap|McCune-Reischauer}}\n| translit_lang1_info4            = Sih\u016dng-si\n| image_skyline                   = Nearoidostation-jan2006.jpg\n| imagesize                       = \n| image_caption                   = [[Wolgot]] Harbor past [[Oido Station]]\n| image_map                       = Gyeonggi-Siheung.svg\n| mapsize                         = \n| map_caption                     = Location in South Korea\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|South Korea}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Regions of Korea|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Seoul National Capital Area|Sudogwon]]\n| population_blank1_title         = Dialect\n| population_blank1               = [[Seoul dialect|Seoul]]\n| area_total_km2                  = 135.79\n| population_as_of                = 2017\n| population_total                = 472162\n| population_density_km2          = 3355.8\n| parts_type                      = [[Administrative divisions of South Korea|Administrative divisions]]\n| parts                           = 11 ''dong''\n| image_blank_emblem              = Siheung logo.png\n| blank_emblem_type               = Emblem of Siheung\n| official_name                   = \n}}\n'''Siheung''' {{IPA-ko|\u0255i.\u0266\u026f\u014b|lang}} is a [[Administrative divisions of South Korea|city]] in [[Gyeonggi]] Province, [[South Korea]].\n\nIn the early [[Three Kingdoms of Korea|Three Kingdoms period]], the Siheung area was part of the [[Baekje]] kingdom.  It was lost to [[Goguryeo]] along with the Han River valley in 475.\n\nSiheung acquired its current administrative identity on January 1, 1989, when the old [[Administrative divisions of South Korea|county]] of Siheung ([[Siheung County]]) was divided into the cities of Siheung, [[Gunpo]], and [[Uiwang]].  At the time Siheung city had a population of only 93,000.  This number more than tripled in the following decade, as massive suburban apartment complexes were developed.\n\nToday's Siheung City area belonged to old [[Incheon]] and Ansan before 1914.\n\nNotable landmarks include [[Oi Island]], [[Mount Sorae]], and the port and inlet of [[Wolgot]].  Siheung includes two [[New town|new cities]] that were developed in the 1990s, [[Sihwa New City|Sihwa]] and [[Wolgot New City]].  The new city of Sihwa includes a very large industrial complex.  Companies headquartered there include [[Hansung Machinery Co.]] [[Korea Polytechnic University]] established in 1997, and also [[Kyonggi Institute of Technology]] established in 1998.\n\nIn 2006, [[Korea Polytechnic University]] built TIP (Techno Innovation Park).  The building has 18 floors used for studying, research, and development for students, faculty, companies and government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kpu.ac.kr/contents/mainEng/eng/tipintro.html|title=KoreaPolytechnicUniversity|website=www.kpu.ac.kr}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010 [[Seoul National University]] acquired 826 thousand square-meters or 204 acres of Siheung property to establish its global campus.<ref>{{cite web |first=Young-jin |last=Chung |url=http://joongangdaily.joins.com/article/view.asp?aid=2916541 |title=Plans under way for new SNU branch in Siheung |publisher=joongangdaily.joins.com |date=2010-02-12 |accessdate=2011-05-05}}</ref>  The university plans to build a bio-medical complex, research hospital, apartments, and education-related infrastructure including lecture halls, dormitories, and an international middle and high school.<ref>{{cite web |first=Yea-rim |last=Kim |url=http://www.koreaittimes.com/story/13492/siheung-road-become-korea%E2%80%99s-investment-mecca |title=Siheung is on the Road to Becoming Korea's Investment Mecca |publisher=koreatimes.com |date=2011-03-16 |accessdate=2011-05-05}}</ref>\n\n==Administrative districts==\nSiheung-si is divided into 18 ''[[Dong(neighbourhood)|dongs]]''<ref name=\"Siheung Administrative districts\">{{cite web|title=Siheung Administrative districts|url=http://www.siheung.go.kr/siheung/%ED%96%89%EC%A0%95%EA%B5%AC%EC%97%AD|accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref>. As of 2017, the population of the city is 419,664 people including 167,802 households. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Administrative dong !! Korean name !! Area(km\u00b2)!! Population !! Household \n|-\n| '''Daeya-dong''' || \ub300\uc57c\ub3d9 || 9.85|| 31,276 || 12.860\n|-\n| '''Sincheon-dong''' || \uc2e0\ucc9c\ub3d9 || 3.44|| 38.566 || 17,898\n|-\n| '''Sinhyun-dong''' || \uc2e0\ud604\ub3d9 || 12.64|| 10,712 || 4,396\n|-\n| '''Eunheng-dong''' || \uc740\ud589\ub3d9 || 5.96|| 44,233 || 15,278\n|-\n| '''Maehwa-dong''' || \ub9e4\ud654\ub3d9 || 11.20|| 12,848 || 5,133\n|-\n| '''Mokgam-dong''' || \ubaa9\uac10\ub3d9 || 17.57|| 40,586 || 15,795\n|-\n| '''Gunja-dong'''|| \uad70\uc790\ub3d9 || 16.69|| 23,735 || 9,738\n|-\n|'''Wolgot-dong'''\n|\uc6d4\uacf6\ub3d9\n|8.53\n|15,358\n|6,859\n|-\n| '''Jeongwangbon-dong'''|| \uc815\uc655\ubcf8\ub3d9 || 8.83|| 21,720 || 14,016\n|-\n| '''Jeongwang 1-dong'''|| \uc815\uc6551\ub3d9 || 6.55|| 23,869 || 13,085\n|-\n| '''Jeongwang 2-dong'''|| \uc815\uc6552\ub3d9 || 5.55|| 32,536 || 12,516\n|-\n| '''Jeongwang 3-dong'''|| \uc815\uc6553\ub3d9 || 6.18|| 23,894 || 10,881\n|-\n| '''Jeongwang 4-dong'''|| \uc815\uc6554\ub3d9 || 5.80|| 22,289 || 7,438\n|-\n|'''Baegot-dong'''\n|\ubc30\uace7\ub3d9\n|4.97\n|68,084\n|25,421\n|-\n| '''Gwarim-dong'''|| \uacfc\ub9bc\ub3d9 || 7.65|| 2,069 || 1,247\n|-\n| '''Yeonseong-dong'''|| \uc5f0\uc131\ub3d9 || 10.05|| 23,368 || 8,283\n|-\n|'''Janggok-dong'''\n|\uc7a5\uace1\ub3d9\n|3.49\n|17,832\n|5.606\n|-\n|'''Neunggok-dong'''|| \ub2a5\uace1\ub3d9 || 4.34|| 17,156 || 6,946\n|-\n|'''Total'''|| \uc2dc\ud765\uc2dc || 135.79|| 472,162 || 186,443\n|}\n\n==Transportation==\n===Railroad===\n*[[Korail]]\n\n;*[[Seoul Subway Line 4]]\n;;;([[Ansan]]) \u2190 [[Jeongwang Station|Jeongwang]] \u2014 [[Oido Station|Oido]]\n;*[[Suin Line]]\n;;;[[Oido Station|Oido]] - [[Darwol Station|Darwol]] - [[Wolgot Station|Wolgot]] \u2192 ([[Namdong-gu]])\n;;* Seohae Line  New subway line built in June 16, 2018.\n;;Siheung Deya - Sincheon - Sinhyeon - Siheung City Hall - Siheung Neunggok are running in Siheung-si.\n\n== Industry ==\n\n=== Gross Domestic Product ===\nThe total regional production of Siheung City in 2012 is 26.888 billion won. It accounts for 3.6% of Gyeonggi Province's GDP. The agriculture and forestry industry (primary industry) is low at 41.4 billion won. Mining and manufacturing (secondary industry) accounted for 16.24 trillion won, accounting for 64.2%, while commercial and service industry (tertiary industry) accounted for 35.6%, amounting to 9.29 trillion won. In the tertiary industry, wholesale and retail trade (6.6 percent), construction (4.0 percent), real estate and leasing (3.3 percent) and business services (3.2 percent)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kosis.kr/statHtml/statHtml.do?orgId=210&tblId=DT_GRDP008&conn_path=I3,|title=KOSIS|website=kosis.kr|language=ko|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Status of Employees by Industry ===\nIn 2014, the total number of workers in Siheung City Industry is 185,032. It accounts for 4.1% of the total number of employees in Gyeonggi-do. The number of agriculture and forestry fisheries (primary industry) is 17, which is low. Mining and manufacturing (secondary industry) accounted for 48.4%, with 89,554 employees. The commercial and service industry (tertiary industry) accounted for 95.6%, accounting for 51.6%. Secondary industry is higher than Gyeonggi province (27.1%) and tertiary industry is lower than Gyeonggi province (72.9%). In the tertiary industry, the proportion of housing and food and lodging (7.6 percent), education (5.2 percent), and health and social services (4.4 percent)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kosis.kr/statHtml/statHtml.do?orgId=210&tblId=DT_21002D003&conn_path=I3,|title=KOSIS|website=kosis.kr|language=ko|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Recreation & Tourism==\n\n*[[Siheung Lotus Theme Park]]\nThe Lotus Theme Park can be visited year-round by bikers and pedestrians, but the peak months for seeing the lotus plants in bloom are July and August.  It is also the site of a summer festival.  Seven varieties of lotus and over thirty varieties of waterlilies are cultivated at the park.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eng.gg.go.kr/1369 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-08-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006140105/http://eng.gg.go.kr/1369 |archivedate=2011-10-06 }} Lotus Theme Park Info</ref> Admission to the theme park during the summer months is free, and lotus viewing tours take place from 9:00&nbsp;a.m. to 2:00&nbsp;p.m. local time.<ref>http://www.siheung.go.kr/tour/content.do?method=contentView&topCmsCd=CM0139&cmsCd=CM1764&grp=2&clickParentNum=11&clickNum=12 Siheung Lotus Theme Park Page (Korean)</ref>  The theme park can be reached by several city bus routes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eng.gg.go.kr/entry/Siheung-Lotus-Theme-Park-1 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-08-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006140637/http://eng.gg.go.kr/entry/Siheung-Lotus-Theme-Park-1 |archivedate=2011-10-06 }} Lotus Theme Park Info and Directions</ref>\n*Siheung Gaetgol Ecology Park\nThere is inland [[mudflat|gaetgol]] that is rare in the world.  This gaetgol is exposed twice a day at low tide. It is called serpentinizing mudflat because it looks like snake.\n\n==Sister cities==\n*{{flagdeco|PRC}} [[Dezhou]], [[Shandong|Shandong,]] China. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dzsyxx.com/Item/25702.aspx|title=\u97e9\u56fd\u59cb\u5174\u5e02\u5e08\u751f\u6765\u6211\u6821\u6e38\u5b66\u8bbf\u95ee\u4ea4\u6d41-\u5fb7\u5dde\u5e02\u5b9e\u9a8c\u5c0f\u5b66|website=www.dzsyxx.com|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://baike.baidu.com/item/%E5%A7%8B%E5%85%B4%E5%B8%82|title=\u59cb\u5174\u5e02|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n*{{flagdeco|US}} [[Rochester, Minnesota|Rochester]], [[Minnesota]], United States<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochestermn.gov/departments/citycouncil/councilmeetings/minutes/102102.htm|title=Regular Adjourned Meeting No. 28|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129065420/http://rochestermn.gov/departments/citycouncil/councilmeetings/minutes/102102.htm|archivedate=2010-11-29}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.siheung.go.kr/english/ City government website]\n\n{{Gyeonggi}}\n{{Metropolitan cities of South Korea}} \n{{Most populous cities in South Korea}}\n{{Coord|37.37986|126.802887|format=dms|display=title|type:city_region:KR-41}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Gyeonggi Province]]\n[[Category:Siheung| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|a city in Gyeonggi-do|a ''dong'' in Geumcheon-gu|Siheung-dong|others|Siheung (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = {{raise|0.1em|Siheung}}\n| native_name                     = {{lower|0.1em|{{lang|ko-Hang|\uc2dc\ud765\uc2dc}}}}\n| translit_lang1                  = Korean\n| settlement_type                 = [[Cities of South Korea|Municipal City]]\n| translit_lang1_t