n\nSiheung acquired its current administrative identity on January 1, 1989, when the old [[Administrative divisions of South Korea|county]] of Siheung ([[Siheung County]]) was divided into the cities of Siheung, [[Gunpo]], and [[Uiwang]].  At the time Siheung city had a population of only 93,000.  This number more than tripled in the following decade, as massive suburban apartment complexes were developed.\n\nToday's Siheung City area belonged to old [[Incheon]] and Ansan before 1914.\n\nNotable landmarks include [[Oi Island]], [[Mount Sorae]], and the port and inlet of [[Wolgot]].  Siheung includes two [[New town|new cities]] that were developed in the 1990s, [[Sihwa New City|Sihwa]] and [[Wolgot New City]].  The new city of Sihwa includes a very large industrial complex.  Companies headquartered there include [[Hansung Machinery Co.]] [[Korea Polytechnic University]] established in 1997, and also [[Kyonggi Institute of Technology]] established in 1998.\n\nIn 2006, [[Korea Polytechnic University]] built TIP (Techno Innovation Park).  The building has 18 floors used for studying, research, and development for students, faculty, companies and government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kpu.ac.kr/contents/mainEng/eng/tipintro.html|title=KoreaPolytechnicUniversity|website=www.kpu.ac.kr}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010 [[Seoul National University]] acquired 826 thousand square-meters or 204 acres of Siheung property to establish its global campus.<ref>{{cite web |first=Young-jin |last=Chung |url=http://joongangdaily.joins.com/article/view.asp?aid=2916541 |title=Plans under way for new SNU branch in Siheung |publisher=joongangdaily.joins.com |date=2010-02-12 |accessdate=2011-05-05}}</ref>  The university plans to build a bio-medical complex, research hospital, apartments, and education-related infrastructure including lecture halls, dormitories, and an international middle and high school.<ref>{{cite web |first=Yea-rim |last=Kim |url=http://www.koreaittimes.com/story/13492/siheung-road-become-korea%E2%80%99s-investment-mecca |title=Siheung is on the Road to Becoming Korea's Investment Mecca |publisher=koreatimes.com |date=2011-03-16 |accessdate=2011-05-05}}</ref>\n\n==Administrative districts==\nSiheung-si is divided into 18 ''[[Dong(neighbourhood)|dongs]]''<ref name=\"Siheung Administrative districts\">{{cite web|title=Siheung Administrative districts|url=http://www.siheung.go.kr/siheung/%ED%96%89%EC%A0%95%EA%B5%AC%EC%97%AD|accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref>. As of 2017, the population of the city is 419,664 people including 167,802 households. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Administrative dong !! Korean name !! Area(km\u00b2)!! Population !! Household \n|-\n| '''Daeya-dong''' || \ub300\uc57c\ub3d9 || 9.85|| 31,276 || 12.860\n|-\n| '''Sincheon-dong''' || \uc2e0\ucc9c\ub3d9 || 3.44|| 38.566 || 17,898\n|-\n| '''Sinhyun-dong''' || \uc2e0\ud604\ub3d9 || 12.64|| 10,712 || 4,396\n|-\n| '''Eunheng-dong''' || \uc740\ud589\ub3d9 || 5.96|| 44,233 || 15,278\n|-\n| '''Maehwa-dong''' || \ub9e4\ud654\ub3d9 || 11.20|| 12,848 || 5,133\n|-\n| '''Mokgam-dong''' || \ubaa9\uac10\ub3d9 || 17.57|| 40,586 || 15,795\n|-\n| '''Gunja-dong'''|| \uad70\uc790\ub3d9 || 16.69|| 23,735 || 9,738\n|-\n|'''Wolgot-dong'''\n|\uc6d4\uacf6\ub3d9\n|8.53\n|15,358\n|6,859\n|-\n| '''Jeongwangbon-dong'''|| \uc815\uc655\ubcf8\ub3d9 || 8.83|| 21,720 || 14,016\n|-\n| '''Jeongwang 1-dong'''|| \uc815\uc6551\ub3d9 || 6.55|| 23,869 || 13,085\n|-\n| '''Jeongwang 2-dong'''|| \uc815\uc6552\ub3d9 || 5.55|| 32,536 || 12,516\n|-\n| '''Jeongwang 3-dong'''|| \uc815\uc6553\ub3d9 || 6.18|| 23,894 || 10,881\n|-\n| '''Jeongwang 4-dong'''|| \uc815\uc6554\ub3d9 || 5.80|| 22,289 || 7,438\n|-\n|'''Baegot-dong'''\n|\ubc30\uace7\ub3d9\n|4.97\n|68,084\n|25,421\n|-\n| '''Gwarim-dong'''|| \uacfc\ub9bc\ub3d9 || 7.65|| 2,069 || 1,247\n|-\n| '''Yeonseong-dong'''|| \uc5f0\uc131\ub3d9 || 10.05|| 23,368 || 8,283\n|-\n|'''Janggok-dong'''\n|\uc7a5\uace1\ub3d9\n|3.49\n|17,832\n|5.606\n|-\n|'''Neunggok-dong'''|| \ub2a5\uace1\ub3d9 || 4.34|| 17,156 || 6,946\n|-\n|'''Total'''|| \uc2dc\ud765\uc2dc || 135.79|| 472,162 || 186,443\n|}\n\n==Transportation==\n===Railroad===\n*[[Korail]]\n\n;*[[Seoul Subway Line 4]]\n;;;([[Ansan]]) \u2190 [[Jeongwang Station|Jeongwang]] \u2014 [[Oido Station|Oido]]\n;*[[Suin Line]]\n;;;[[Oido Station|Oido]] - [[Darwol Station|Darwol]] - [[Wolgot Station|Wolgot]] \u2192 ([[Namdong-gu]])\n;;* Seohae Line  New subway line built in June 16, 2018.\n;;Siheung Deya - Sincheon - Sinhyeon - Siheung City Hall - Siheung Neunggok are running in Siheung-si.\n\n== Industry ==\n\n=== Gross Domestic Product ===\nThe total regional production of Siheung City in 2012 is 26.888 billion won. It accounts for 3.6% of Gyeonggi Province's GDP. The agriculture and forestry industry (primary industry) is low at 41.4 billion won. Mining and manufacturing (secondary industry) accounted for 16.24 trillion won, accounting for 64.2%, while commercial and service industry (tertiary industry) accounted for 35.6%, amounting to 9.29 trillion won. In the tertiary industry, wholesale and retail trade (6.6 percent), construction (4.0 percent), real estate and leasing (3.3 percent) and business services (3.2 percent)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kosis.kr/statHtml/statHtml.do?orgId=210&tblId=DT_GRDP008&conn_path=I3,|title=KOSIS|website=kosis.kr|language=ko|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Status of Employees by Industry ===\nIn 2014, the total number of workers in Siheung City Industry is 185,032. It accounts for 4.1% of the total number of employees in Gyeonggi-do. The number of agriculture and forestry fisheries (primary industry) is 17, which is low. Mining and manufacturing (secondary industry) accounted for 48.4%, with 89,554 employees. The commercial and service industry (tertiary industry) accounted for 95.6%, accounting for 51.6%. Secondary industry is higher than Gyeonggi province (27.1%) and tertiary industry is lower than Gyeonggi province (72.9%). In the tertiary industry, the proportion of housing and food and lodging (7.6 percent), education (5.2 percent), and health and social services (4.4 percent)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kosis.kr/statHtml/statHtml.do?orgId=210&tblId=DT_21002D003&conn_path=I3,|title=KOSIS|website=kosis.kr|language=ko|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Recreation & Tourism==\n\n*[[Siheung Lotus Theme Park]]\nThe Lotus Theme Park can be visited year-round by bikers and pedestrians, but the peak months for seeing the lotus plants in bloom are July and August.  It is also the site of a summer festival.  Seven varieties of lotus and over thirty varieties of waterlilies are cultivated at the park.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eng.gg.go.kr/1369 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-08-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006140105/http://eng.gg.go.kr/1369 |archivedate=2011-10-06 }} Lotus Theme Park Info</ref> Admission to the theme park during the summer months is free, and lotus viewing tours take place from 9:00&nbsp;a.m. to 2:00&nbsp;p.m. local time.<ref>http://www.siheung.go.kr/tour/content.do?method=contentView&topCmsCd=CM0139&cmsCd=CM1764&grp=2&clickParentNum=11&clickNum=12 Siheung Lotus Theme Park Page (Korean)</ref>  The theme park can be reached by several city bus routes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eng.gg.go.kr/entry/Siheung-Lotus-Theme-Park-1 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-08-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006140637/http://eng.gg.go.kr/entry/Siheung-Lotus-Theme-Park-1 |archivedate=2011-10-06 }} Lotus Theme Park Info and Directions</ref>\n*Siheung Gaetgol Ecology Park\nThere is inland [[mudflat|gaetgol]] that is rare in the world.  This gaetgol is exposed twice a day at low tide. It is called serpentinizing mudflat because it looks like snake.\n\n==Sister cities==\n*{{flagdeco|PRC}} {{citation needed span|[[Dezhou]], [[Shandong]], China|date=July 2018}}\n*{{flagdeco|US}} [[Rochester, Minnesota|Rochester]], [[Minnesota]], United States<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rochestermn.gov/departments/citycouncil/councilmeetings/minutes/102102.htm|title=Regular Adjourned Meeting No. 28|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129065420/http://rochestermn.gov/departments/citycouncil/councilmeetings/minutes/102102.htm|archivedate=2010-11-29}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.siheung.go.kr/english/ City government website]\n\n{{Gyeonggi}}\n{{Metropolitan cities of South Korea}} \n{{Most populous cities in South Korea}}\n{{Coord|37.37986|126.802887|format=dms|display=title|type:city_region:KR-41}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Gyeonggi Province]]\n[[Category:Siheung| ]]\n", "name_user": "Kingjames1004", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSister cities:missing source added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siheung"}
{"title_page": "The Zygon Inversion", "text_new": "{{Infobox Doctor Who episode\n| number             = 258b\n| serial_name        = The Zygon Inversion\n| show               = DW\n| type               = episode\n| image              = The Zygon Inversion.png\n| image_size         = 275px\n| caption            = Official poster for the episode\n| doctor             = [[Peter Capaldi]] ([[Twelfth Doctor]])\n| companion          = [[Jenna Coleman]] ([[Clara Oswald]])\n| guests             = \n*[[Ingrid Oliver]] \u2013 [[List of UNIT personnel#Petronella Osgood|Osgood]]\n*[[Jemma Redgrave]] \u2500 [[List of UNIT personnel#Kate Stewart|Kate Stewart]]\n*Nicholas Asbury \u2013 Etoine\n*Aidan Cook \u2013 Zygon\n*Tom Wilton \u2013 Zygon\n*Jack Parker \u2013 Zygon\n*[[Nicholas Briggs]] \u2013 Voice of the Zygons\n| director           = Daniel Nettheim\n| writer             = [[Peter Harness]]<br>[[Steven Moffat]]\n| script_editor      = David P Davis\n| producer           = [[Peter Bennett (producer)|Peter Bennett]]\n| executive_producer = Steven Moffat<br>Brian Minchin\n| composer           = [[Murray Gold]]\n| series             = [[Doctor Who (series 9)|Series 9]]\n| length             = 2nd of 2-part story, 46 minutes\n| date               = {{Start date|2015|11|7|df=y}}\n| preceding          = \"[[The Zygon Invasion]]\"\n| following          = \"[[Sleep No More (Doctor Who)|Sleep No More]]\"\n}}\n\"'''The Zygon Inversion'''\" is the eighth episode of the [[Doctor Who (series 9)|ninth series]] of the British [[science fiction television]] series ''[[Doctor Who]]''. It was first broadcast on [[BBC One]] on 7 November 2015. It is written by [[Peter Harness]] and [[Steven Moffat]] and directed by Daniel Nettheim. The episode is the second of a two-parter, the first being \"[[The Zygon Invasion]]\" on 31 October.\n\nSet in present-day London, the episode involves Bonnie, the leader of a splinter group of shapeshifting aliens called Zygons, taking the form of a human called [[Clara Oswald|Clara]] (played by [[Jenna Coleman]]). Bonnie intends to use an object called the Osgood Box to unmask 20 million Zygons on Earth, thereby starting a war against humanity.\n\n==Plot==\nIn the present, Bonnie, the leader of a splinter group of shapeshifting [[Zygon]]s, has taken [[Clara Oswald|Clara]]'s form, keeping her body in a pod. Clara finds herself in a dream version of her flat, able to control Bonnie's actions to a small degree due to a telepathic connection between them, giving the [[Twelfth Doctor]] and [[UNIT]] scientist [[List of UNIT personnel#Petronella Osgood|Osgood]] time to parachute out of their plane before Bonnie shoots it down.\n\nThe Doctor and Osgood land on a beach. Controlling Bonnie's hand, Clara sends a message to the Doctor's phone saying \"I'm awake.\" The Doctor video calls Bonnie. From winks Bonnie exhibits, the Doctor recognises that Clara is telling him her pod is in London. In interrogating Clara via their telepathic connection, Bonnie learns the Osgood Box is in the UNIT Black Archive under the [[Tower of London]]. Against the wishes of the Zygons who are not aligned with the splinter group, Bonnie intends to start a war against humanity by using the Osgood Box to unmask 20 million Zygons on Earth. UNIT leader [[List of UNIT personnel#Kate Stewart|Kate Stewart]], having survived the encounter with the Zygon in New Mexico,{{refn|group=N|As depicted in the previous week's episode, \"[[The Zygon Invasion]]\".}} reconvenes with the Doctor and Osgood in London.\n\n[[File:Doctor Who Experience (30641597640).jpg|left|thumb|The two Osgood Boxes, as shown at the Doctor Who Experience.]]\nBonnie discovers that there are two identical Osgood Boxes in the Archive, only differing by colour. By the time the Doctor, Osgood, and Kate arrive, Bonnie has found that either box's button reveals a second set of two buttons within. When Bonnie prepares to press a button on the blue box, which would either unmask the Zygons or make their human forms permanent, Kate prepares to do the same on the red box, which would destroy either every Zygon or everyone in London. The Doctor tries to talk both of them out of this action \u2013 the Osgood Boxes have been a means to assure peace because of the consequences of declaring a war. Eventually, after the Doctor admits the consequences he had to live with since the [[Time War (Doctor Who)|Time War]], both Bonnie and Kate back off with the former realising the boxes are empty and were only a ploy to avoid a disaster. The Doctor wipes Kate's memories to keep the peace treaty. Bonnie calls off the splinter group and says they will live peacefully. Later, the Doctor offers Osgood a chance to ride in the [[TARDIS]], but she refuses and instead reveals her new duplicate \u2013 Bonnie, who has taken a new form after giving up Clara.\n\n===Continuity===\nKate Stewart describes her gunfire while escaping an attacking Zygon as \"five rounds rapid\". This is a phrase closely associated with Kate's father, the [[Brigadier Lethbridge-Stewart|Brigadier]], that he first used in ''[[The D\u00e6mons]]'' (1971).<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/4mfZTZ6PTHB0wZD9jN1bv1s/the-zygon-inversion-the-fact-file|title=BBC One \u2013 Doctor Who, Series 9, The Zygon Inversion \u2013 The Zygon Inversion: The Fact File|work=BBC}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Fourth Doctor]]'s companion [[Harry Sullivan (Doctor Who)|Harry Sullivan]] is mentioned in this episode by name (he was only alluded to in the prior episode) as developing Z67 \u2013 \"Sullivan's Gas\" \u2013 as a means of stopping the Zygons.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/the-zygon-inversion-hints-teasers-set-2-77716.htm|title=The Zygon Inversion: Hints & Teasers (Set #2)|work=doctorwhotv.co.uk}}</ref>  The Doctor also refers to Sullivan as \"the imbecile\", a reference to the Fourth Doctor serial ''[[Revenge of the Cybermen]]'', where the Doctor shouted \"Harry Sullivan is an imbecile!\" after Sullivan triggered a rockslide and then tried to remove a Cyberbomb from the Doctor without deactivating the [[booby trap]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/tv/doctor-who/37682/doctor-who-series-9-geeky-spots-in-the-zygon-inversion|title=Doctor Who series 9: geeky spots in The Zygon Inversion|work=Den of Geek}}</ref><ref name=\"bbcamerica.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbcamerica.com/anglophenia/2015/11/doctor-who-10-things-you-may-not-know-about-the-zygon-inversion/|title='Doctor Who': 10 Things You May Not Know About 'The Zygon Inversion' \u2013 Anglophenia \u2013 BBC America|work=BBC America}}</ref>\n\nUNIT's Black Archive, first seen in \"[[The Day of the Doctor]]\" (2013) and containing items from several past episodes, currently has a Mire battle helmet first seen in \"[[The Girl Who Died]]\" (2015).<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n \nThe Doctor claims that he himself planned to use a box with a button to commit mass murder. This is a reference to \"The Day of the Doctor\" when three of the Doctor's past incarnations planned to use the Moment, a [[Time Lords|Time Lord]] doomsday device, to end the [[Time War (Doctor Who)|Time War]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nOsgood says that there has been more than one meaning for the acronym ''TARDIS''. The 'D' in [[TARDIS]] has been given as both \"''dimension''\" and \"''dimensions''\" during both the classic series and the revival, giving the name ''TARDIS'' two different meanings.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/> In \"[[The Next Doctor]]\" (2008), Jackson Lake says his 'TARDIS'\u2014in reality, a hot air balloon\u2014stands for \u201cTethered Aerial Release Developed In Style\u201d.<ref name=\"bbcamerica.com\"/> In this episode, the Doctor gives it yet another meaning: \"Totally And Radically Driving In Space\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcmbuzz.com/2015/11/07/doctor-who-s09e08-the-zygon-inversion-review/|title=MCM BUZZ \u2013 Movies, TV, Comics, Gaming, Anime, Cosplay News & Reviews \u00bb Doctor Who S09E08 \"The Zygon Inversion\" REVIEW|work=MCM BUZZ \u2013 Movies, TV, Comics, Gaming, Anime, Cosplay News & Reviews}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/recap/doctor-who-season-9-episode-8/2|title=Doctor Who recap: The Zygon Inversion - EW.com|work=ew.com}}</ref>\n\nAs he departs, the Doctor tells the Osgoods that \"I'm a very big fan\", the same thing Osgood says to the [[Eleventh Doctor]] in \"The Day of the Doctor\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/12-great-moments-from-the-zygon-inversion-part-1-77788.htm|title=12 Great Moments From The Zygon Inversion (Part 1)|work=doctorwhotv.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Outside references===\nThe Doctor's [[Union Jack]] parachute prototype (calling it \"camouflage... we're in Britain.\") is a direct reference to the pre-titles sequence of the 1977 [[James Bond]] film ''[[The Spy Who Loved Me (film)|The Spy Who Loved Me]]'', in which Bond jumps from a cliff and expands a parachute with the same design.<ref name = 'James Bond reference'>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-11-07/did-you-spot-the-james-bond-reference-in-doctor-who-the-zygon-inversion|title = Did you spot the James Bond reference in Doctor Who The Zygon Inversion?|work=[[Radio Times]]|year=2015|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Doctor calls Bonnie \"Zygella\", a pun on chef [[Nigella Lawson]]'s name.<ref name=\"bbcamerica.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.us/tv/doctor-who/250361/doctor-who-the-zygon-inversion-reference-guide|title=Doctor Who: The Zygon Inversion reference guide|work=Den of Geek}}</ref>\n\nBonnie is asked by the Doctor about the \"brave new world\" her revolution will create, citing [[William Shakespeare]]'s play ''[[The Tempest]]'': \"O brave new world, that has such people in it\".<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nThe Doctor borrows the phrase \"And I mean that most sincerely\" from the UK television show ''[[Opportunity Knocks (UK TV series)|Opportunity Knocks]]''.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\n==Broadcast and reception==\nThe episode was watched by 4.22 million viewers overnight in the UK, a 20.4% audience share. It received an [[Appreciation Index]] score of 84.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Zygon Inversion \u2013 AI:84 |website=Doctor Who News |url= http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2015/11/the-zygon-inversion-ai84.html}}</ref> The final ratings were 6.03 million viewers with a 25.1% audience share.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://guide.doctorwhonews.net/story.php?story=TheZygonInvasion/2|title=Doctor Who Guide: The Zygon Inversion|work=Doctor Who Guide|accessdate=November 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n{{TV ratings\n<!-- Aggregate scores -->\n| aggregate1 = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] (Tomatometer)\n| aggregate1score = 95%<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/doctor_who/s09/e08/|title=The Zygon Inversion|date=12 December 2018|work=rottentomatoes.com}}</ref>\n| aggregate2 = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] (Average Score)\n| aggregate2score = 8.12<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\" />\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| rev3 = [[The A.V. Club]]\n| rev3Score = A<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/doctor-who-makes-its-closing-argument-against-war-227871|title=\"The Zygon Inversion\" \u00b7 Doctor Who \u00b7 TV Review Doctor Who makes its closing argument against war \u00b7 TV Club \u00b7 The A.V. Club|work=avclub.com}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''Paste Magazine''\n| rev4Score = 8.8<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/11/doctor-who-review-the-zygon-inversion.html|title=Doctor Who Review: \"The Zygon Inversion\"|work=pastemagazine.com}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''SFX Magazine''\n| rev5Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/doctor-who-s908-zygon-inversion-review/|title=Doctor Who S9.08 \u2013 \"The Zygon Inversion\" review|author=Richard Edwards|date=7 November 2015|work=GamesRadar+}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''TV Fanatic''\n| rev6Score = {{rating|2.5|5|score=2.7/5 stars}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvfanatic.com/2015/11/doctor-who-season-9-episode-8-review-the-zygon-inversion/|title=Doctor Who|author=MelaniePond|work=TV Fanatic}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''IndieWire''\n| rev7Score = A++<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/review-doctor-who-season-9-episode-8-the-zygon-inversion-faces-truth-and-consequences-20151107|title=Review: 'Doctor Who' Season 9 Episode 8, 'The Zygon Inver \u2013 Indiewire|author=Kaite Welsh|date=8 November 2015|work=Indiewire}}</ref>\n| rev8 = [[IGN]]\n| rev8Score = 7.9<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/11/07/doctor-who-the-zygon-inversion-review|title=Doctor Who: \"The Zygon Inversion\" Review|author=Scott Collura|date=7 November 2015|work=IGN}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''New York Magazine''\n| rev9Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2015/11/doctor-who-recap-season-9-episode-8.html|title=Doctor Who Recap: The Bonnie Situation|work=Vulture}}</ref>\n| rev10 = [[Daily Telegraph]]\n| rev10Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/doctor-who/11980503/doctor-who-zygon-inversion-review-recap-jenna-coleman.html|title=Doctor Who: The Zygon Inversion: 6 things we learnt, plus a sneak peek at next week's episode|author=Tim Martin|date=9 November 2015|work=Telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n| rev11 = [[Radio Times]]\n| rev11Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-11-07/doctor-who-the-zygon-inversion-review-peter-capaldi-triumphs-in-a-soul-searching-peace-negotiation-for-our-times|title=Doctor Who series 9 episode 8 review: Peter Capaldi triumphs in a soul-searching peace negotiation for our times|author=Patrick Mulkern|work=RadioTimes}}</ref>\n}}\n\"The Zygon Inversion\" received positive reviews, with many highlighting Capaldi and Coleman's performances and the episode's political themes as its best attributes. On review aggregator, [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the episode has a 95% positive review rating and a score of 8/10, with a critical consensus stating, \"While \"The Zygon Inversion\" isn't the most compelling conclusion to a Doctor Who two-parter, it allows for a stirring performance by Capaldi while hinting at Clara's fate in the episodes to come.\"<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\" />\n\nSteven Cooper of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' called it the best episode of the season so far and claimed it was \"a powerful conclusion to the story set up last week\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/house/article/doctor-who-recap-season-9-episode-8-the-zygon-inversion|title= Doctor Who Recap|work= Slant Magazine}}</ref> Mark Rozeman of ''[[Paste Magazine]]'' praised the transformation from \"standard aliens-invade plot line\" to \"a treatise about war and its ultimate uselessness.\" He ultimately awarded the episode an 8.8.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/11/doctor-who-review-the-zygon-inversion.html|title = Doctor Who Review: The Zygon Inversion|work= Paste Magazine}}</ref> Kaite Welsh of ''IndieWire'' heavily acclaimed the episode, awarding it an A++ grade and saying that the episode was \"Less overtly political than the previous episode, this week is an embarrassment of riches\". She further praised Coleman's performance by saying that the episode \"could very well be Jenna Coleman's goodbye present\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Welsh|first1=Kaite|title=Review: 'Doctor Who' Season 9 Episode 8, 'The Zygon Inversion,' Faces Truth and Consequences|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/review-doctor-who-season-9-episode-8-the-zygon-inversion-faces-truth-and-consequences-20151107|website=IndieWire|publisher=Kaite Welsh|accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref> Mark Rozeman of ''Paste Magazine'' awarded the episode a score of 8.8 out of ten, praising Clara and Bonnie's sequences as \"brilliantly contrived\". He also praised Capaldi's performance, stating \"it\u2019s a firm reminder of how lucky we are that an actor of Peter Capaldi\u2019s caliber has taken the titular role and so thoroughly made it his own\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rozeman|first1=Mark|title=Doctor Who Review: \"The Zygon Inversion\"|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/11/doctor-who-review-the-zygon-inversion.html|website=Paste Magazine|publisher=Mark Rozeman|accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nWriting for ''[[The Guardian]]'', Dan Martin also heavily praised the episode, specifically the Doctor's anti-war speech in the episode's conclusion. He stated \"This Doctor has never been written better, Capaldi has never channelled Tom Baker more, that sequence is cemented instantly as the 'Capaldi moment' in clip shows for the rest of time\", and while he said that \"It was a risky game to attempt the sort of contemporary allegory\" that the episode did, he soon confirmed that the episode \"knocked [it] out of the park\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Martin|first1=Dan|title=Doctor Who series 35, episode eight: The Zygon Inversion|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/nov/07/doctor-who-series-35-episode-eight-the-zygon-inversion|website=The Guardian|publisher=Dan Martin|accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref> Alasdair Wilkins of [[The A.V. Club]] also acclaimed the episode, awarding it a perfect \"A\" grade \u2013 the third of the season. He began his review by saying \"The climax of 'The Zygon Inversion' makes explicit something that the best anti-war Doctor Who stories have always understood. Depicting the madness of war doesn\u2019t require an epic scale. If anything, narrowing the focus to a single conflict or moral dilemma clarifies the essential futility of violent conflict\". He then closed his review by claiming \"The simplicity of [the] setup allows this two-parter to be one of the show's strongest ever statements against war, not because the Doctor is challenging us from on high to live up to his standard, but rather because he wants no one else to know his pain\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wilkins|first1=Alasdair|title=Doctor Who makes its closing argument against war|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/doctor-who-makes-its-closing-argument-against-war-227871|website=The A.V. Club|publisher=Alasdair Wilkins|accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref> Den of Geek praised \u2033The Zygon Inversion\u2033 as the best episode of the current series, and named it, \u2033one of the best pieces of screen entertainment of the year, full stop.\u2033\n\nThe episode aired a week after the crash of [[Metrojet Flight 9268]] in Egypt, and resulted in 31 complaints to the [[Office of Communications]] (Ofcom) because of the scene depicting a plane being shot down. Viewers argued that the scene was inappropriate in the aftermath of the crash, but Ofcom decided not to launch an investigation. The regulator concluded that \"the science fiction nature of Doctor Who and the storyline created a sufficient distinction from recent events\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Mark |last=Sweney |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/nov/23/doctor-who-cleared-by-ofcom-airliner-the-zygon-inversion?subid=15276612&CMP=ema_546 |title=Doctor Who cleared over 'insensitive' airliner scene despite 31 complaints |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=23 November 2015 |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=N}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Twelfth Doctor}}\n*{{BBCDWnew|year=2015|id=b06phcqv|title=The Zygon Inversion}}\n*{{TardisIndexFile |The Zygon Inversion (TV story)|\"The Zygon Inversion\"}}\n\n*{{IMDb episode|4652846|The Zygon Inversion}}\n\n{{Doctor Who episodes|N9}}\n{{Doctor Who episodes by Steven Moffat}}\n{{Zygon stories}}\n{{UNIT stories}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zygon Inversion}}\n[[Category:Twelfth Doctor episodes]]\n[[Category:2015 British television episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes written by Steven Moffat]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Peter Harness]]\n[[Category:UNIT serials]]\n[[Category:Doctor Who stories set on Earth]]\n[[Category:British television episodes in multiple parts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Doctor Who episode\n| number             = 258b\n| serial_name        = The Zygon Inversion\n| show               = DW\n| type               = episode\n| image              = The Zygon Inversion.png\n| image_size         = 275px\n| caption            = Official poster for the episode\n| doctor             = [[Peter Capaldi]] ([[Twelfth Doctor]])\n| companion          = [[Jenna Coleman]] ([[Clara Oswald]])\n| guests             = \n*[[Ingrid Oliver]] \u2013 [[List of UNIT personnel#Petronella Osgood|Osgood]]\n*[[Jemma Redgrave]] \u2500 [[List of UNIT personnel#Kate Stewart|Kate Stewart]]\n*Nicholas Asbury \u2013 Etoine\n*Aidan Cook \u2013 Zygon\n*Tom Wilton \u2013 Zygon\n*Jack Parker \u2013 Zygon\n*[[Nicholas Briggs]] \u2013 Voice of the Zygons\n| director           = Daniel Nettheim\n| writer             = [[Peter Harness]]<br>[[Steven Moffat]]\n| script_editor      = David P Davis\n| producer           = [[Peter Bennett (producer)|Peter Bennett]]\n| executive_producer = Steven Moffat<br>Brian Minchin\n| composer           = [[Murray Gold]]\n| series             = [[Doctor Who (series 9)|Series 9]]\n| length             = 2nd of 2-part story, 45 minutes\n| date               = {{Start date|2015|11|7|df=y}}\n| preceding          = \"[[The Zygon Invasion]]\"\n| following          = \"[[Sleep No More (Doctor Who)|Sleep No More]]\"\n}}\n\"'''The Zygon Inversion'''\" is the eighth episode of the [[Doctor Who (series 9)|ninth series]] of the British [[science fiction television]] series ''[[Doctor Who]]''. It was first broadcast on [[BBC One]] on 7 November 2015. It is written by [[Peter Harness]] and [[Steven Moffat]] and directed by Daniel Nettheim. The episode is the second of a two-parter, the first being \"[[The Zygon Invasion]]\" on 31 October.\n\nSet in present-day London, the episode involves Bonnie, the leader of a splinter group of shapeshifting aliens called Zygons, taking the form of a human called [[Clara Oswald|Clara]] (played by [[Jenna Coleman]]). Bonnie intends to use an object called the Osgood Box to unmask 20 million Zygons on Earth, thereby starting a war against humanity.\n\n==Plot==\nIn the present, Bonnie, the leader of a splinter group of shapeshifting [[Zygon]]s, has taken [[Clara Oswald|Clara]]'s form, keeping her body in a pod. Clara finds herself in a dream version of her flat, able to control Bonnie's actions to a small degree due to a telepathic connection between them, giving the [[Twelfth Doctor]] and [[UNIT]] scientist [[List of UNIT personnel#Petronella Osgood|Osgood]] time to parachute out of their plane before Bonnie shoots it down.\n\nThe Doctor and Osgood land on a beach. Controlling Bonnie's hand, Clara sends a message to the Doctor's phone saying \"I'm awake.\" The Doctor video calls Bonnie. From winks Bonnie exhibits, the Doctor recognises that Clara is telling him her pod is in London. In interrogating Clara via their telepathic connection, Bonnie learns the Osgood Box is in the UNIT Black Archive under the [[Tower of London]]. Against the wishes of the Zygons who are not aligned with the splinter group, Bonnie intends to start a war against humanity by using the Osgood Box to unmask 20 million Zygons on Earth. UNIT leader [[List of UNIT personnel#Kate Stewart|Kate Stewart]], having survived the encounter with the Zygon in New Mexico,{{refn|group=N|As depicted in the previous week's episode, \"[[The Zygon Invasion]]\".}} reconvenes with the Doctor and Osgood in London.\n\n[[File:Doctor Who Experience (30641597640).jpg|left|thumb|The two Osgood Boxes, as shown at the Doctor Who Experience.]]\nBonnie discovers that there are two identical Osgood Boxes in the Archive, only differing by colour. By the time the Doctor, Osgood, and Kate arrive, Bonnie has found that either box's button reveals a second set of two buttons within. When Bonnie prepares to press a button on the blue box, which would either unmask the Zygons or make their human forms permanent, Kate prepares to do the same on the red box, which would destroy either every Zygon or everyone in London. The Doctor tries to talk both of them out of this action \u2013 the Osgood Boxes have been a means to assure peace because of the consequences of declaring a war. Eventually, after the Doctor admits the consequences he had to live with since the [[Time War (Doctor Who)|Time War]], both Bonnie and Kate back off with the former realising the boxes are empty and were only a ploy to avoid a disaster. The Doctor wipes Kate's memories to keep the peace treaty. Bonnie calls off the splinter group and says they will live peacefully. Later, the Doctor offers Osgood a chance to ride in the [[TARDIS]], but she refuses and instead reveals her new duplicate \u2013 Bonnie, who has taken a new form after giving up Clara.\n\n===Continuity===\nKate Stewart describes her gunfire while escaping an attacking Zygon as \"five rounds rapid\". This is a phrase closely associated with Kate's father, the [[Brigadier Lethbridge-Stewart|Brigadier]], that he first used in ''[[The D\u00e6mons]]'' (1971).<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/4mfZTZ6PTHB0wZD9jN1bv1s/the-zygon-inversion-the-fact-file|title=BBC One \u2013 Doctor Who, Series 9, The Zygon Inversion \u2013 The Zygon Inversion: The Fact File|work=BBC}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Fourth Doctor]]'s companion [[Harry Sullivan (Doctor Who)|Harry Sullivan]] is mentioned in this episode by name (he was only alluded to in the prior episode) as developing Z67 \u2013 \"Sullivan's Gas\" \u2013 as a means of stopping the Zygons.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/the-zygon-inversion-hints-teasers-set-2-77716.htm|title=The Zygon Inversion: Hints & Teasers (Set #2)|work=doctorwhotv.co.uk}}</ref>  The Doctor also refers to Sullivan as \"the imbecile\", a reference to the Fourth Doctor serial ''[[Revenge of the Cybermen]]'', where the Doctor shouted \"Harry Sullivan is an imbecile!\" after Sullivan triggered a rockslide and then tried to remove a Cyberbomb from the Doctor without deactivating the [[booby trap]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/tv/doctor-who/37682/doctor-who-series-9-geeky-spots-in-the-zygon-inversion|title=Doctor Who series 9: geeky spots in The Zygon Inversion|work=Den of Geek}}</ref><ref name=\"bbcamerica.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbcamerica.com/anglophenia/2015/11/doctor-who-10-things-you-may-not-know-about-the-zygon-inversion/|title='Doctor Who': 10 Things You May Not Know About 'The Zygon Inversion' \u2013 Anglophenia \u2013 BBC America|work=BBC America}}</ref>\n\nUNIT's Black Archive, first seen in \"[[The Day of the Doctor]]\" (2013) and containing items from several past episodes, currently has a Mire battle helmet first seen in \"[[The Girl Who Died]]\" (2015).<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n \nThe Doctor claims that he himself planned to use a box with a button to commit mass murder. This is a reference to \"The Day of the Doctor\" when three of the Doctor's past incarnations planned to use the Moment, a [[Time Lords|Time Lord]] doomsday device, to end the [[Time War (Doctor Who)|Time War]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nOsgood says that there has been more than one meaning for the acronym ''TARDIS''. The 'D' in [[TARDIS]] has been given as both \"''dimension''\" and \"''dimensions''\" during both the classic series and the revival, giving the name ''TARDIS'' two different meanings.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/> In \"[[The Next Doctor]]\" (2008), Jackson Lake says his 'TARDIS'\u2014in reality, a hot air balloon\u2014stands for \u201cTethered Aerial Release Developed In Style\u201d.<ref name=\"bbcamerica.com\"/> In this episode, the Doctor gives it yet another meaning: \"Totally And Radically Driving In Space\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcmbuzz.com/2015/11/07/doctor-who-s09e08-the-zygon-inversion-review/|title=MCM BUZZ \u2013 Movies, TV, Comics, Gaming, Anime, Cosplay News & Reviews \u00bb Doctor Who S09E08 \"The Zygon Inversion\" REVIEW|work=MCM BUZZ \u2013 Movies, TV, Comics, Gaming, Anime, Cosplay News & Reviews}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/recap/doctor-who-season-9-episode-8/2|title=Doctor Who recap: The Zygon Inversion - EW.com|work=ew.com}}</ref>\n\nAs he departs, the Doctor tells the Osgoods that \"I'm a very big fan\", the same thing Osgood says to the [[Eleventh Doctor]] in \"The Day of the Doctor\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/12-great-moments-from-the-zygon-inversion-part-1-77788.htm|title=12 Great Moments From The Zygon Inversion (Part 1)|work=doctorwhotv.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Outside references===\nThe Doctor's [[Union Jack]] parachute prototype (calling it \"camouflage... we're in Britain.\") is a direct reference to the pre-titles sequence of the 1977 [[James Bond]] film ''[[The Spy Who Loved Me (film)|The Spy Who Loved Me]]'', in which Bond jumps from a cliff and expands a parachute with the same design.<ref name = 'James Bond reference'>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-11-07/did-you-spot-the-james-bond-reference-in-doctor-who-the-zygon-inversion|title = Did you spot the James Bond reference in Doctor Who The Zygon Inversion?|work=[[Radio Times]]|year=2015|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Doctor calls Bonnie \"Zygella\", a pun on chef [[Nigella Lawson]]'s name.<ref name=\"bbcamerica.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.us/tv/doctor-who/250361/doctor-who-the-zygon-inversion-reference-guide|title=Doctor Who: The Zygon Inversion reference guide|work=Den of Geek}}</ref>\n\nBonnie is asked by the Doctor about the \"brave new world\" her revolution will create, citing [[William Shakespeare]]'s play ''[[The Tempest]]'': \"O brave new world, that has such people in it\".<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nThe Doctor borrows the phrase \"And I mean that most sincerely\" from the UK television show ''[[Opportunity Knocks (UK TV series)|Opportunity Knocks]]''.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\n==Broadcast and reception==\nThe episode was watched by 4.22 million viewers overnight in the UK, a 20.4% audience share. It received an [[Appreciation Index]] score of 84.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Zygon Inversion \u2013 AI:84 |website=Doctor Who News |url= http://www.doctorwhonews.net/2015/11/the-zygon-inversion-ai84.html}}</ref> The final ratings were 6.03 million viewers with a 25.1% audience share.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://guide.doctorwhonews.net/story.php?story=TheZygonInvasion/2|title=Doctor Who Guide: The Zygon Inversion|work=Doctor Who Guide|accessdate=November 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n{{TV ratings\n<!-- Aggregate scores -->\n| aggregate1 = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] (Tomatometer)\n| aggregate1score = 95%<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/doctor_who/s09/e08/|title=The Zygon Inversion|date=12 December 2018|work=rottentomatoes.com}}</ref>\n| aggregate2 = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] (Average Score)\n| aggregate2score = 8.12<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\" />\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| rev3 = [[The A.V. Club]]\n| rev3Score = A<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/doctor-who-makes-its-closing-argument-against-war-227871|title=\"The Zygon Inversion\" \u00b7 Doctor Who \u00b7 TV Review Doctor Who makes its closing argument against war \u00b7 TV Club \u00b7 The A.V. Club|work=avclub.com}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''Paste Magazine''\n| rev4Score = 8.8<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/11/doctor-who-review-the-zygon-inversion.html|title=Doctor Who Review: \"The Zygon Inversion\"|work=pastemagazine.com}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''SFX Magazine''\n| rev5Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/doctor-who-s908-zygon-inversion-review/|title=Doctor Who S9.08 \u2013 \"The Zygon Inversion\" review|author=Richard Edwards|date=7 November 2015|work=GamesRadar+}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''TV Fanatic''\n| rev6Score = {{rating|2.5|5|score=2.7/5 stars}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvfanatic.com/2015/11/doctor-who-season-9-episode-8-review-the-zygon-inversion/|title=Doctor Who|author=MelaniePond|work=TV Fanatic}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''IndieWire''\n| rev7Score = A++<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/review-doctor-who-season-9-episode-8-the-zygon-inversion-faces-truth-and-consequences-20151107|title=Review: 'Doctor Who' Season 9 Episode 8, 'The Zygon Inver \u2013 Indiewire|author=Kaite Welsh|date=8 November 2015|work=Indiewire}}</ref>\n| rev8 = [[IGN]]\n| rev8Score = 7.9<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/11/07/doctor-who-the-zygon-inversion-review|title=Doctor Who: \"The Zygon Inversion\" Review|author=Scott Collura|date=7 November 2015|work=IGN}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''New York Magazine''\n| rev9Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2015/11/doctor-who-recap-season-9-episode-8.html|title=Doctor Who Recap: The Bonnie Situation|work=Vulture}}</ref>\n| rev10 = [[Daily Telegraph]]\n| rev10Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/doctor-who/11980503/doctor-who-zygon-inversion-review-recap-jenna-coleman.html|title=Doctor Who: The Zygon Inversion: 6 things we learnt, plus a sneak peek at next week's episode|author=Tim Martin|date=9 November 2015|work=Telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n| rev11 = [[Radio Times]]\n| rev11Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-11-07/doctor-who-the-zygon-inversion-review-peter-capaldi-triumphs-in-a-soul-searching-peace-negotiation-for-our-times|title=Doctor Who series 9 episode 8 review: Peter Capaldi triumphs in a soul-searching peace negotiation for our times|author=Patrick Mulkern|work=RadioTimes}}</ref>\n}}\n\"The Zygon Inversion\" received positive reviews, with many highlighting Capaldi and Coleman's performances and the episode's political themes as its best attributes. On review aggregator, [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the episode has a 95% positive review rating and a score of 8/10, with a critical consensus stating, \"While \"The Zygon Inversion\" isn't the most compelling conclusion to a Doctor Who two-parter, it allows for a stirring performance by Capaldi while hinting at Clara's fate in the episodes to come.\"<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\" />\n\nSteven Cooper of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' called it the best episode of the season so far and claimed it was \"a powerful conclusion to the story set up last week\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/house/article/doctor-who-recap-season-9-episode-8-the-zygon-inversion|title= Doctor Who Recap|work= Slant Magazine}}</ref> Mark Rozeman of ''[[Paste Magazine]]'' praised the transformation from \"standard aliens-invade plot line\" to \"a treatise about war and its ultimate uselessness.\" He ultimately awarded the episode an 8.8.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/11/doctor-who-review-the-zygon-inversion.html|title = Doctor Who Review: The Zygon Inversion|work= Paste Magazine}}</ref> Kaite Welsh of ''IndieWire'' heavily acclaimed the episode, awarding it an A++ grade and saying that the episode was \"Less overtly political than the previous episode, this week is an embarrassment of riches\". She further praised Coleman's performance by saying that the episode \"could very well be Jenna Coleman's goodbye present\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Welsh|first1=Kaite|title=Review: 'Doctor Who' Season 9 Episode 8, 'The Zygon Inversion,' Faces Truth and Consequences|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/review-doctor-who-season-9-episode-8-the-zygon-inversion-faces-truth-and-consequences-20151107|website=IndieWire|publisher=Kaite Welsh|accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref> Mark Rozeman of ''Paste Magazine'' awarded the episode a score of 8.8 out of ten, praising Clara and Bonnie's sequences as \"brilliantly contrived\". He also praised Capaldi's performance, stating \"it\u2019s a firm reminder of how lucky we are that an actor of Peter Capaldi\u2019s caliber has taken the titular role and so thoroughly made it his own\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rozeman|first1=Mark|title=Doctor Who Review: \"The Zygon Inversion\"|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/11/doctor-who-review-the-zygon-inversion.html|website=Paste Magazine|publisher=Mark Rozeman|accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nWriting for ''[[The Guardian]]'', Dan Martin also heavily praised the episode, specifically the Doctor's anti-war speech in the episode's conclusion. He stated \"This Doctor has never been written better, Capaldi has never channelled Tom Baker more, that sequence is cemented instantly as the 'Capaldi moment' in clip shows for the rest of time\", and while he said that \"It was a risky game to attempt the sort of contemporary allegory\" that the episode did, he soon confirmed that the episode \"knocked [it] out of the park\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Martin|first1=Dan|title=Doctor Who series 35, episode eight: The Zygon Inversion|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/nov/07/doctor-who-series-35-episode-eight-the-zygon-inversion|website=The Guardian|publisher=Dan Martin|accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref> Alasdair Wilkins of [[The A.V. Club]] also acclaimed the episode, awarding it a perfect \"A\" grade \u2013 the third of the season. He began his review by saying \"The climax of 'The Zygon Inversion' makes explicit something that the best anti-war Doctor Who stories have always understood. Depicting the madness of war doesn\u2019t require an epic scale. If anything, narrowing the focus to a single conflict or moral dilemma clarifies the essential futility of violent conflict\". He then closed his review by claiming \"The simplicity of [the] setup allows this two-parter to be one of the show's strongest ever statements against war, not because the Doctor is challenging us from on high to live up to his standard, but rather because he wants no one else to know his pain\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wilkins|first1=Alasdair|title=Doctor Who makes its closing argument against war|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/doctor-who-makes-its-closing-argument-against-war-227871|website=The A.V. Club|publisher=Alasdair Wilkins|accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref> Den of Geek praised \u2033The Zygon Inversion\u2033 as the best episode of the current series, and named it, \u2033one of the best pieces of screen entertainment of the year, full stop.\u2033\n\nThe episode aired a week after the crash of [[Metrojet Flight 9268]] in Egypt, and resulted in 31 complaints to the [[Office of Communications]] (Ofcom) because of the scene depicting a plane being shot down. Viewers argued that the scene was inappropriate in the aftermath of the crash, but Ofcom decided not to launch an investigation. The regulator concluded that \"the science fiction nature of Doctor Who and the storyline created a sufficient distinction from recent events\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Mark |last=Sweney |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/nov/23/doctor-who-cleared-by-ofcom-airliner-the-zygon-inversion?subid=15276612&CMP=ema_546 |title=Doctor Who cleared over 'insensitive' airliner scene despite 31 complaints |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=23 November 2015 |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=N}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Twelfth Doctor}}\n*{{BBCDWnew|year=2015|id=b06phcqv|title=The Zygon Inversion}}\n*{{TardisIndexFile |The Zygon Inversion (TV story)|\"The Zygon Inversion\"}}\n\n*{{IMDb episode|4652846|The Zygon Inversion}}\n\n{{Doctor Who episodes|N9}}\n{{Doctor Who episodes by Steven Moffat}}\n{{Zygon stories}}\n{{UNIT stories}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zygon Inversion}}\n[[Category:Twelfth Doctor episodes]]\n[[Category:2015 British television episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes written by Steven Moffat]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Peter Harness]]\n[[Category:UNIT serials]]\n[[Category:Doctor Who stories set on Earth]]\n[[Category:British television episodes in multiple parts]]\n", "name_user": "LegoKeoni", "label": "safe", "comment": "Amended running time", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Zygon_Inversion"}
